<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali National Strike Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The armed national strike called
by Nepal's ultra-leftist guerrillas on Thursday ended almost
peacefully, with no reports of violence in the country.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued late Thursday by the Home Ministry said
no violent activities took place in the country and people's daily
life was almost normal.
</P>
<P>
The guerrillas called a compulsory strike across the country to
protest the alleged killings of guerrilla members by the police
and to commemorate the 10th anniversary of the democratic movement
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Under the threat of violence against those who ignore the call
of strike, nearly all activities in the country were stopped --
offices,schools and shops were closed while traffic and
transportations were almost paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
At least 7,000 additional armed police personnel were deployed
across the nation to respond to any violent incidents and to SOS
calls during the strike.
</P>
<P>
About 1300 people, including police, guerrillas and civilians
have been killed in police-guerrilla clashes since the ultra-
leftist guerrillas started armed struggles in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
