<HEADLINE> FIFA Endeavor in Fight Against Bosman Ruling - Blatter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 6 (Xinhua) -- International Football Federation
(FIFA) President Sepp Blatter said here on Thursday that the world
soccer's governing body will endeavor to exercise the disruptive
impact brought about by the Bosman ruling.
</P>
<P>
"Rich and poor clubs are clearly categorized and the gap
between them is widened by the Bosman ruling," Blatter said. "
This is not in the conformance to the soccer logic which should be
based on the spirit of unification and democracy.
</P>
<P>
"The disruptive impact of the ruling must be stamped out," said
the FIFA chief, who arrived here on Thursday for a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
"I hope our efforts will yield some results by the end of the
year," he added.
</P>
<P>
Before the 1995 Bosman ruling, players were bound to a club
until their contract was sold. As a consequence, the number of
foreign players pitched at one time was limited to three with
another two on the roster for each team in most leagues.
</P>
<P>
But things changed when Belgian midfielder Jean-Marc Bosman
said he should be free to move, without payment to his club, at
the end of his contract. He won his case before the European
Court of Justice, and his example, called the Bosman Ruling,
effectively ended the limits on foreigners within the European
Union and created free agency for European athletes.
</P>
<P>
Soccer bodies are disturbed by the trend of talents being
assembled in the hands of a few rich European clubs. Small clubs
are unable to recover the cost of developing young talents since
the players can wait until the expiration of their contracts to
sign with a bigger club.
</P>
<P>
The EU commission on January rejected a proposal by Blatter to
introduce a new system requiring each team field at least six
players who are eligible for the respective country's national
squad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
