<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Govt Denies Negotiation With Opposition Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal
Mocumbi on Thursday denied that there are any negotiations between
his government and the main opposition party Renamo.
</P>
<P>
Renamo (Mozambican National Resistance) leader Afonso Dhlakama
on Wednesday claimed that negotiations were taking place on
holding early general elections, or securing governorships for
Renamo in those provinces where it won a majority in the last
December elections.
</P>
<P>
However, Mocumbi told a press briefing that he knew nothing of
such negotiations, adding: "There are no negotiations between the
government and any political party."
</P>
<P>
He also denied the constant claims by Renamo parliamentary
deputies that there is "a political crisis" in the country.
</P>
<P>
If anybody was preparing "situations of crisis and
instability", then the law would deal firmly with them, he warned.
</P>
<P>
Renamo accused the ruling Frelimo party of fraud in general
elections last December and threatened to form a separate
government in the six provinces where it won a majority unless the
government agreed to recount ballots and hold negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
