<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Approves Republican Budget for Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate, by a near
party line vote of 51 to 45, approved Friday a Republican-written
budget of 1.83 trillion U.S. dollars for fiscal year 2001, moving
lawmakers a step closer to a campaign season full of battles with
President Bill Clinton over spending and taxes.
</P>
<P>
Since the House approved a similar budget two weeks ago, the
Republicans' goal is for Congress to pass a compromise measure by
next Friday, in time for lawmakers' spring recess.
</P>
<P>
The budget, which does not require Clinton's signature, only
sets overall tax and spending targets for fiscal year 2001, which
starts on October, 2000.
</P>
<P>
In Friday's most notable Democrat victory, senators voted 51-49
to chip 2.7 billion dollars out of the Republicans' five-year, 150-
billion-dollar tax cut to use for Pell college grants for low-
income students.
</P>
<P>
Even before the Senate completed its plan, the two parties were
attacking each others' fiscal visions.
</P>
<P>
Democrats said the proposed Republican tax cut would consume
virtually the entire budget surplus, not counting Social Security
money.
</P>
<P>
Like Clinton proposed, the Republican budget would trim the 3.6-
trillion-dollar publicly held national debt by about 1 trillion
dollars over the next five years, a reduction that most economists
say should help the economy by helping to keep interest rates low.
</P>
<P>
Republicans would also boost spending for education, biomedical
research and other programs. But such details are really decided
in later bills.
</P>
<P>
By voice vote, senators agreed Thursday to add another 4
billion dollars to next year's defense budget for a total of 311
billion dollars, or 7 percent above this year and 5 billion
dollars more than Clinton's proposal.
</P>
<P>
The provision would compensate for a 4-billion-dollar Pentagon
boost the House approved in a separate emergency spending bill
that Senate Republican leaders have decided to scuttle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
