<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crime Rises in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Over 11,500 criminal cases were
handled by the Angolan judiciary last year, marking an increase of
24 percent as compared with the previous year, Angola's top
prosecutor said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency Angop quoted the Angolan Attorney
General Domingos Calulo as saying that the southwest African
country had suffered a "dizzying" escalation of crime last year.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to a four-day meeting of the Angolan magistrates in
the northwest enclave of Cabinda, Calulo said of the 11,507
criminal cases, nearly 4,000 cases took place in Luanda, whose
five judges were " absolutely insufficient" to handle such a load.
</P>
<P>
"Only with the creation of new courts can we improve the
quality of the magistrates' work and speed up court procedures,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
