<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Mobile Telephone Clients Up to 14,000: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Telecommunication
Corporation (ETC) has got 14,000 mobile telephone clients while
all available internet lines have been leased to clients, the
Walta Information Center reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The launching of mobile and internet services with an outlay of
over 130 million birr (about 16.2 million U.S. dollars) has
enabled the country to have better information exchange links with
the outside world, ETC Deputy General Manager Taddele Gurara was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The mobile telephone system introduced with an outlay of 110
million birr (about 13.7 million U.S. dollars) has the capacity
to serve 36,000 clients, Taddele said.
</P>
<P>
Continuing its expansion of mobile and internet services, ETC
has already completed studies for introducing message receiving
and transmitting devices in mobile telephones as well as for
stream lining internet and fax services, the general manager
said, adding this will go into effect next month.
</P>
<P>
Taddele also disclosed that a new system has been devised for
enabling permanent employees working for the government, private
or international organizations to acquire mobile telephones by
making payments spread over a one year period instead of all at
once.
</P>
<P>
According to Taddele, efforts are underway for making
additional installations intended to expand services outside
Addis Ababa to as far as Nazareth and Sodere, two towns about 100
kilometers southeast of the capital, and beyond in the next three
months.
</P>
<P>
It was also reported that internet lines made operational at a
cost of over 20 million birr (2.4 million U.S. dollars) have all
been leased to 2, 600 clients, Taddele said, noting that there are
over 1,500 applicants on the waiting list.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said, a sum of 103.3 million U.S. dollars has been
pledged by the United Nations Development Program and ETC for
increasing internet lines to 14,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
