<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Hails Constitutional Amendment Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
on Friday hailed its parliament's approval of the Constitutional
Amendment Bill which empowers the government to acquire land from
white farmers without compensation.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said with the institution of the amendments, Zimbabweans
had acquired sovereignty to determine their future.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a rally of the ruling Zimbabwe African
National Union-Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf) in Bindura, about 100
kilometers from Harare.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Today is a historic day because we are celebrating
victory over imperialism and colonialism," adding that the people
can now say the land belongs to them. "This is a victory to
enhance our sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the white farmers had betrayed themselves by
rejecting the draft constitution which made Britain liable for
compensation.
</P>
<P>
"But now with the new law the government has the power to
acquire the land without compensation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will only recognize the responsibility to pay for
structures and other developments," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would not acquire all land belonging to
the whites but only half of that land.
</P>
<P>
About 4,000 white commercial farmers own about 12 million
hectares of fertile land while the government needs at least five
million hectares to resettle the landless black families.
</P>
<P>
"We are no longer going to ask for the land but we are going to
take without negotiating," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said if white people wanted to move out of Zimbabwe they
were free to do so, scorning at reports that Britain was ready to
pull its citizens out of the country.
</P>
<P>
"If they want to go we will open the borders for them. We will
give them police escort," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who has kicked off Zanu-pf campaigns for parliamentary
elections, told supporters that the government would soon set the
exact dates for the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
