<HEADLINE> Kremlin Declares All PACE Visits to Chechnya Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Russian president's aide Sergey
Yastrzhembsky announced Friday that all visits by the
Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe (PACE)
representatives and its leaders to Chechnya will be banned.
</P>
<P>
As a response to the Thursday decision by PACE to suspend
Russia's membership in the Europe Council, Moscow has decided to
stop "visits to Chechnya by PACE delegations, including its
leaders," Yastrzhembsky told a briefing in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
"If before PACE could play a certain role in processes in
Russia,now this door has been shut," the Kremlin aide said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that "emotions explicitly prevailed over common
sense" when PACE members discussed the situation in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
"We set no equation sign between PACE and the Council of Europe
as well as between PACE and Europe as a whole," said Yastrzhembsky.
</P>
<P>
Moscow is profoundly disappointed that "deputies in Strasbourg
did not grasp the simple truth that cooperation is essential not
only for Russia but also for the Council of Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the position of Russia remains unchanged: "
the anti-terrorist operation will be continued."
</P>
<P>
"We do not intend to enter a discussion on basic values such as
the integrity of a country and the fight against terrorism," the
aide said. 
</P>
