<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Minister Calls for Blood Donation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Deputy Health Minister
Ernest Mwansa urged here Friday the country's citizens to donate
blood, saying that "blood can be available to us in the hour of
need only if we donate blood regularly. "
</P>
<P>
He told a rally to mark World Health Day falling on April 7
that many people have misgivings that donating blood weakens a
person or there are some kind of risks involved. It has been
proven beyond any doubt that donating blood does not weaken a
person in any manner.
</P>
<P>
He said that his country requires 60,000 units of blood
annually while it is able to collect only about 43,000 units.
</P>
<P>
In Zambia 60 percent of blood requirement is met through
voluntary donors while the remaining 40 percent is met from family
members of those in need, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that in Zambia all the blood collected is tested for
HIV, hepatitis and syphilis and about 10 percent of blood
collected is discarded due to contamination.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said that the country has adopted a
national blood policy and the blood transfusion act is awaiting
approval by parliament.
</P>
<P>
Eight new blood transfusion centers have been built and are
well- equipped, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
