<HEADLINE> Thousands of Genocide Victim Remains Re-Buried in Mass Grave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of the 1994 genocide
victims' remains were on Friday re-buried in a mass grave at a
memorial site in Rwanda's capital Kigali to mark the sixth
anniversary of the tragedy, Rwanda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to establish a genocide memorial site in
each of 150 communes where the genocide took place. Over 800,000
minority Tutsis and moderate Hutus were killed by Hutu extremists
during the 100-day genocide starting on April 7,1994.
</P>
<P>
"Genocide in Rwanda was a result of poor political ideologies
that emphasized ethnic differences. The political leaders of the
time deliberately ignored many things that we have in common:
language, culture, marriage ties and peaceful co-existance, that
had for long been a fundamental pillar of Rwandan society,"
Rwanda's interim President Paul Kagame said at the memorial site.
</P>
<P>
"The 1994 genocide victims' remains have to be buried so as to
keep in mind what happened to Rwanda. The whole world should
understand the hard times Rwanda went through and draw a lesson
from Rwanda," Kagame added.
</P>
<P>
"We must have a well functioning judiciary, which will be the
greatest support that the government can give to all Rwandans, so
that all genocide perpetrators are tried, " he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
