<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Peace Talks End Without Substantial Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The five-day talks between the
Sudanese government and southern rebels aimed at ending the
17-year civil war closed without substantial progress in the
Kenyan capital Nairobi Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nafie Ali Nafie, peace advisor to the Sudanese President, told
a press conference here Friday afternoon that this round of talks
focused on political issues -- the separation of religion and
state as well as the right of self-determination in the south.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government delegation led by Nafie held lengthy
discussions with the representatives of the Sudan People's
Liberation Movement (SPLM), Nafie told the press.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, he said the two sides also discussed such
issues as administrative system, national legislation, judicial
system and revenue system, among others.
</P>
<P>
This week's meeting was the latest in several rounds of largely
 fruitless talks that have taken place under the auspice of a
sub-committee of the Intergovernmental Authority on Development
(IGAD).
</P>
<P>
At the press briefing, Nafie did not disclose the date when the
next round of talks will resume.
</P>
<P>
The previous round of talks between the two parties was held in
Nairobi in February, ending without agreement.
</P>
<P>
It seems that the gap in the positions between the government
and the rebels on the issues discussed in the rounds of talks
still remained unbridged. 
</P>
