<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Apologizes to Rwandans for not Stopping Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Belgian Prime Minister Guy
Verhofstandt said on Friday that he is sorry that Belgium has done
nothing to stop the Rwandan genocide, Rwanda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the commemoration at Gisozi suburb of the Rwandan
capital Kigali where about 200,000 remains of the 1994 genocide
were reburied over the past week to mark the sixth anniversary of
the massacre, he said that the international community is
responsible for what happened in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"I accept the role of Belgium in the genocide that happened
here, Belgium and the United Nations should apologize to Rwandans
for having done nothing to stop the genocide, they very well knew
what was going to happen," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian Prime Minister said that he and his delegation have
come to pay tribute to the 10 Belgian soldiers and all other
Rwandans who perished in genocide.
</P>
<P>
He said that all genocide suspects who are hiding in his
country will have to be tried by the International Criminal
Tribunal for Rwanda. He assured support to Rwanda in restoring
peace, unity and reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian delegation of over 100 people on Friday morning
laid flowers on the graves of 10 Belgian U.N. soldiers who were
killed shortly after the plane carrying the then Rwandan president
Habyalimana was brought down on April 6, 1994.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda's interim President Paul Kagame thanked the Belgian
delegation in general and the prime minister in particular for the
courage he took to ask for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from the Democratic Republic of the Congo and
Burundi also took part in the commemoration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
