<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Rate Unchanged in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The nation's unemployment rate
held steady at 4.1 percent in March, even as 416,000 workers found
jobs, the largest number in four years, the Labor Department said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
In February, only 7,000 new jobs were created, much weaker than
the 43,000 previously reported by the government.
</P>
<P>
Government analysts said a number of special factors boosted
payrolls, including the hiring of 117,000 temporary census workers
and a longer five-week survey period in March vs. the normal four-
week period. The last five-week survey period was in 1972.
</P>
<P>
Job growth last month was slightly stronger than the 400,000-
job range many analysts were expecting. But government analysts
said that taking all the special factors into account, job growth
was probably roughly in line with the average monthly gain for
1999. Those analysts estimated that the extra week in the survey
period added anywhere from 50,000 to 100,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Jobs gains were fairly widespread last month.
</P>
<P>
The service sector, the driving force of job creation in the
United States, added 328,000 jobs in March. Business services
added 150,000 jobs last month, while the government added 142,000,
led by the hiring of 117,000 workers to conduct the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing, which lost around 248,000 jobs last year, lost 5,
000 jobs in March. Government analysts said the March decline
would have been greater had it not been for the return of 15,000
aircraft workers who had been on strike in February.
</P>
<P>
Construction companies added 89,000 jobs, reflecting some of
the seasonal hiring that normally occurs and the longer survey
period.
</P>
<P>
Average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures,
rose 0.4 percent to 13.60 U.S. dollars in March. In February,
wages grew by 0.4 percent, slightly higher than the 0.3 percent
increase the government initially reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
