<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Rebuffs PACE Decision to Suspend Its Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Moscow on Friday kicked back the
Thursday decision by the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of
Europe (PACE) to suspend Russia's membership in the Europe Council
on the excuse of "bad human rights situation in Chechnya."
</P>
<P>
The resolution "will certainly harm dialogue between Russia and
the assembly," Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said at a
Friday meeting with the European Union's Troika representatives in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
"The assembly was misled by members who still think in terms of
the cold war," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moscow is stunned by and deeply regrets the PACE decision but "
will continue its policy of eradicating international terrorism,
working out a political settlement in the Chechen republic and
restoring a constitutional order and human rights there," Ivanov
said.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has "taken note of the desire expressed by heads of
state and government of European Union countries to cooperate with
Russia on the basis of common values for peace, stability and
prosperity in Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
A statement, released by the Russian Foreign Ministry on Friday,
also said the PACE resolution "delivered a serious blow to the
Council of Europe's' efforts to develop a common European area in
humanitarian and legal spheres among others."
</P>
<P>
PACE "demonstrated disrespect for the memory of the Russians
who fell victim to Chechen terrorists and those who gave up their
lives for the restoration of peace and calm to Chechnya, for the
territorial integrity of Russia," it continued.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the unprecedented openness of the Russian dialogue,
the demonstration of more than convincing evidence of the real
state of affairs in Chechnya and the firm line of the Russian
leadership to a political settlement, the PACE deputies could not
or did not want to take that into account. They continue to
collect their information from the false propaganda circulated by
Chechen terrorists and their patrons," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Russia "will continue to firmly follow the policy of uprooting
international terrorism, achieving a lasting political settlement
in Chechnya, restoring constitutional law, order, and a normal
social and economic life in the republic," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
