<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Registrations In Britain Up In First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Commercial vehicle registrations
remained positive, recording overall growth in March, according to
figures released Friday by the Society of Motor Manufacturers and
Traders (SMMT).
</P>
<P>
Total registrations in March increased 7.2 percent to 42,239
compared with March 1999's performance of 39,409 units.
Registrations in the first quarter rose 7.3 percent on the same
period last year to 77876 units from 72553.
</P>
<P>
This partly reflects relative weakness in the first quarter of
1999, due to economic stagnation, anticipation of the 1999 Budget
and uncertainty over the twice-yearly plate change, the SMMT said.
</P>
<P>
However, new registrations for Rover fell by more than 1,000 to
24,899 in March from the same month in 1999 and for the year to
date are running 6.38 percent lower.
</P>
<P>
There have been calls for a boycott of German car maker, BMW,
after its decision to sell Rover to a venture capital firm, with
the loss of thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
Christopher Macgrowan, SMMT Chief Executive said "Even though
there was a degree of uncertainty in the first quarter of 1999,
which undermined demand, the increase seen in the first three
months of this year is undoubtedly welcome."
</P>
<P>
"This is a far stronger performance than was anticipated a few
months ago, a development no doubt helped by the strong economy,
competitive market and continuing growth of e-commerce," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
