<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2nd APEC Education Ministerial Meetings Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The 2nd APEC Education
Ministerial Meeting wound up its two-day session Friday by issuing
a joint statement titled "Education for Learning Societies in the
21st Century."
</P>
<P>
The statement says that the education ministers agreed that the
theme of "Education for Learning Societies in the 21st Century"
speaks of the APEC's aspiration of providing education for all,
for life and that life-learning will be the characteristic of this
society.
</P>
<P>
It says the ministers affirmed that education can play an
important role in shaping a learning society, while information
technology is essential in a learning society.
</P>
<P>
The ministers attached great importance to teachers who are at
the heart of education, saying that teaching profession should
enjoy respect within society so that the profession will continue
to draw able and committed individuals to it and teachers can
perform their role more effectively.
</P>
<P>
On the reform in education system, the statement says, the
ministers held that all sectors within APEC economies should have
access to an affordable education while effective school
leadership, management of education systems and the requisite
resources must be set in place.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are of the consensus that the monitoring and
evaluation of outcomes will be an essential component of education
management systems, it adds.
</P>
<P>
The ministers have identified four strategic areas as the next
steps in transforming their education systems to become the
foundation and impetus for "Learning Societies in the 21st Century
" with a view to realize people's hope for life-long self-
improvement.
</P>
<P>
They are to acknowledge IT as a core competency for students of
the future and harness the potential of IT to enhance teaching and
learning and stimulate life-long learning, to enhance the quality
of teaching and teacher development and to make teacher become the
model of learning individual, to cultivate sound management
practices among policy-makers and practitioners in education to
ensure the achievement of access, affordability and quality of
education to all and to promote a culture of active engagement
among APEC member economies in education and to energize and
enrich their continuing efforts for improving their education at
local and regional levels.
</P>
<P>
The ministers declared their intent to meet once every five
years and agreed to APEC Human Resource Development Working Group'
s decision to rename the APEC Education Forum as the APEC
Education Network (EDNET).  
</P>
</TEXT>
