<HEADLINE> India Imposes Custom Duty on Rice, Fruits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government Friday
imposed customs duty up to 80 percent on rice varieties and some
fruits to restrict cheap imports of these commodities in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Consumers Affairs and Public Distribution Minister Shanta Kumar
said that the government imposed 80 percent customs duty on rice
in husk, husked (brown) and broken rice from nil import duty. The
duty on milled rice would now be 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
There would be 50 percent customs duty on maize seed, grain
sorghum, millet and spelt which was being imported freely till
Friday, Kumar added.
</P>
<P>
The government has also raised duties on fresh grapes from 25
to 35 percent and on apples from 35 to 50 percent. 
</P>
