<TEXT>
<P>
The matter was being considered and a final decision was
expected to be taken soon, Home Minister L. K. Advani said Friday
in Chandigarh, 235 kilometers northwest of here, the Press Trust
of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
Indian hardliners have been pressing for a stop of the railway
link between the two countries, and the only bus service between
New Delhi and Lahore in Pakistan, which was open into service
following a historic bus trip to Pakistan by Indian Prime Minister
Atal Bihari Vajpayee in February last year.
</P>
<P>
Advani ruled out once again an immediate resumption of the
stalled dialogue with Pakistan, saying that no purpose would be
served even if talks were held while innocents were being killed
in Kashmir and cross-border terrorism was carried on, according to
PTI.
</P>
<P>
