<HEADLINE> S. African Force to Have New Weapons: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- South African National
Defense Force (SANDF) will have to be equipped with new weapons to
meet the rescue or peacekeeping missions in the future, South
African Defense Minister Mosiuoa Lekota said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Introducing debate on his budget vote in the National Assembly
in Cape Town, Lekota said the defense function is about developing
and maintaining a capability to ward off threats or dangers
created by human beings or natural forces to South Africa and its
people.
</P>
<P>
The most memorable record of South Africa's defense capability
in recent times was the coverage by media throughout the world of
SANDF personnel and aircraft carrying out rescue missions in
Mozambique, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said that "these were SANDF personnel performing their duty
as our nation expected of them."
</P>
<P>
However, the capital equipment of the SANDF has reached a state
of block obsolescence, Lekota said, adding that the ships,
submarines and aircraft will become obsolete by 2004 or 2005 and
will be maintained until they can be replaced with
newer-generation equipment.
</P>
<P>
"The department of defense will henceforth embark on the
planned capital renewal program for the South African army, which
will primarily constitute a domestic acquisition program," he
said. 
</P>
