<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Refuses to Accept Obligations From Zimbabwe's Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The British High Commission in
Zimbabwe Friday said that it will not accept the obligations
imposed by Zimbabwe's Constitutional Amendment Number 16 on
Britain.
</P>
<P>
"We obviously fully recognize the right of the people of
Zimbabwe to draw up their own constitution. But equally obvious a
sovereign and independent state can not use its constitution to
impose conditions on another," the commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The parliament of Zimbabwe Thursday passed the Constitution of
Zimbabwe Bill (No. 16) which seeks to amend the Lancaster House
Constitution and allow the Zimbabwean government to compulsorily
acquire land for resettlement without paying any compensation.
</P>
<P>
Successive British governments had made substantial
contributions to the first phase of land reform in Zimbabwe, the
commission said, stressing that Britain had met all the
obligations agreed at the time of the independence in relation to
land.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to supporting a transparent, fair and cost
effective program of land reform," the commission said. "This is
part of our commitment to support programs in Zimbabwe and
elsewhere to reduce poverty."
</P>
<P>
According to the commission, Britain is willing to fund a
program of land reform on the basis that it deals with real
poverty and is within the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
Land ownership in Zimbabwe is in favor of whites who hold large
swathes of the prime farming land while more than 70 percent of
black Zimbabweans are congested in infertile wastelands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
