<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most People Lack Access to Safe Blood, Says WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- An overwhelming majority of the
world's population does not have access to safe blood, the World
Health Organization (WHO) warned here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Despite all the technological marvels that humanity is
experiencing, reliable and safe blood supply is still out of reach
for untold millions of people around the world," WHO Director-
General Gro Harlem Brundtland said in a statement marking the
World Health Day.
</P>
<P>
WHO called on its 191 members and on the international
community to address urgently this glaring inequality.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Day is observed on April 7 each year to mark
the day in 1948 when WHO was founded. This year's theme, "Safe
Blood Starts With Me," highlights the highly unbalanced situation
in the world today with regard to blood supply.
</P>
<P>
Between 5 percent and 10 percent of HIV infections worldwide
are transmitted through the transfusion of infected blood and
blood products, according to WHO and the United Nations Program on
HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS). They estimate that 5.6 million new HIV
infections occur annually.
</P>
<P>
Another important issue is the inappropriate and unnecessary
use of blood especially where clear clinical guidelines are not
available, WHO said.
</P>
<P>
The major diseases other than HIV that can be transmitted by
infected blood are the hepatitis B and C viruses, syphilis,
malaria and Chagas disease, amongst others. Each year, unsafe
transfusion and injection practices cause an estimated 8-16
million hepatitis B virus infections, 2.3-4.7 million hepatitis C
virus infections, and 80,000- 160,000 HIV infections, according to
WHO.
</P>
<P>
Some 75 million units (one unit generally equals 450
milliliters) of blood are donated each year throughout the world,
but more than 13 million of those units are not tested for all
transfusion-transmissible infections.
</P>
<P>
In 1975, WHO's governing body, the World Health Assembly,
passed a resolution urging WHO members to "promote development of
national blood services based on voluntary non-remunerated
donation of blood." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
