<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- France expressed its strong regret
Friday over the air raids by U.S. and British warplanes in
southern Iraq Thursday, in which 14 civilians were killed and 19
injured.
</P>
<P>
"The useless and deadly bombings are dismaying," said
spokeswoman of the French Foreign Ministry Anne Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that up to 175 civilians have been killed and
nearly 500 injured by U.S.-British air raids since they began in
January 1999.
</P>
<P>
She said the strikes would not help create an atmosphere for
realizing the objectives of the United Nations Security Council
and its resolution 1284, which calls for a renewal of U.N. arms
inspection in Iraq and an alleviation of U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine Thursday again called
for a lifting of the sanctions on Iraq, which he said was "
inefficient and cruel" toward the Iraqi people. 
