<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Work on Asian Games Bid Presses Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 7 (Xinhua) - Hong Kong's Asian Games Bid
Committee has been working in full steam in the past month to
press ahead with the preparation for Hong Kong's bid for the 2006
Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
The bid committee held its second meeting here on Friday.
Committee members were informed that the original deadline for the
submission of bids had been postponed by the Olympic Council of
Asia (OCA), from May 31 to June 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
Four cities have indicated their intention to bid for the Games
-- Kuala Lumpur of Malaysia, New Delhi of India, Doha of Qatar and
Hong Kong. Each of the candidate cities will have the opportunity
to give a short presentation at the Annual Meeting of the National
Olympic Committees to be held in Rio De Janeiro next month.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Sports Association for the Physically Disabled
will also bid for the right to host the 2006 Far East and South
Pacific Games for the Disabled (FESPIC Games). If Hong Kong wins
both bids, the FESPIC Games would be held shortly after the Asian
Games and use the same facilities.
</P>
<P>
The Bid Committee considered at the meeting the progress
reports of its three sub-committees.
</P>
<P>
The Committee also examined the draft bid document prepared by
the Bid Document Sub-Committee, giving its views and suggestions
to improve the document's layout and presentation.
</P>
<P>
The Events and Venues Sub-Committee noted with delight that
various private organizations have pledged their support by
offering their venues and facilities for hosting the Games. This
will give additional flexibility to the planning work of the
Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
