<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SDB Pledges 29 Billion Yuan for Yunnan's Key Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The State Development Bank (SDB)
will provide 29 billion yuan (about 3.49 billion US dollars) in
loan over the next two to three years to southwest China's Yunnan
Province for the construction of key projects.
</P>
<P>
SDB President Chen Yuan and Yunnan Governor Li Jiating signed
an agreement of intent here on the loan today.
</P>
<P>
This is one of several huge-sum loans pledged recently by the
bank. Earlier it signed similar agreements on multi-billion-yuan
loans for two other western provinces -- Sichuan and Guizhou --
and Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after signing the protocol, Chen Yuan
said Chinese financial institutions are very supportive of the
country's strategy of developing west China, and they have all
increased their capital support for the western provinces and
Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
Founded in March 1994, the SDB is the largest policy bank in
China, with assets totaling 600 billion yuan. It aims to offer
help to key local and state projects for infrastructure
construction.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, it has begun to extend preferential treatment
to central and western counties; loans to these areas account for
some 70 percent of its total loans.
</P>
<P>
Under today's agreement, the loans will be used for Yunnan's 15
key projects, in the fields of highways, railways, electricity,
telecommunications and urban construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
