<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Female Scientists Owe Success to Aspiration, Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Female scientists belief that they
depend on aspiration and effort to become successful rather than
talent, according to a recent survey released by the Science Times
today.
</P>
<P>
The questionnaire survey was conducted by the Department of
Sociology of the Shandong University on 18 female academicians at
the Chinese Academy of Sciences and the Chinese Academy of
Engineering, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
Answering the mailed questionnaires, 14 academicians gave
themselves the highest grades in terms of "clear goals and
aspirations" and "hard work and reading", while 15 of them wrote
zero in terms of talent.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that these female scientists have been
keeping a good balance between career and family, and many of them
play leading roles in their families as well as in their
workplaces.
</P>
<P>
Eight academicians said that they spend more time on housework
than their husbands, six said they share the household chores with
their husbands, and four said they do less.
</P>
<P>
All the scientists surveyed have a strong sense of equality
between men and women, but most of them thought that female
scientific workers are not as well employed as their male
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The academicians, all of whom are over 60 years old, also
provided their opinions on the situation of women in scientific
and technological research fields during the past 20 years. But
more said the situation is not as good as in the 1950s and 1960s
than those who said it has improved.
</P>
<P>
Only half of the scientists believe that the status of female
scientific workers will improve in the country in the near future,
and the other eight said they are just not so optimistic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNIFIL Not Mandated to Disarm Palestinians in Lebanon: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Interim Force in
Lebanon (UNIFIL) said Friday that it has no mandate to disarm the
Palestinians in refugee camps in the country, An-Nahar newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
UNIFIL spokesman Timor Goksel said the Palestinian refugee camps
were outside UNIFIL's area of operation in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese President Emile Lahoud said in a memorandum after
talking here with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's envoy Roid
Larsen that the U.N. peacekeepers should disarm Palestinian
refugees in Lebanon after Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud expressed concern that Palestinian guerrillas would
continue attacks after Israel's unilateral withdrawal from south
Lebanon. Lebanese government can not entirely control Palestinian
guerrillas so they will not be responsible for the possible
attacks, he hinted.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know why this is being said in connection with UNIFIL.
We are a peacekeeping force, not a deterrent force." Goksel said.
</P>
<P>
He also added that UNIFIL still has no word on how the Israeli
army would withdraw from south Lebanon or how long the withdrawal
process would take.
</P>
<P>
"In order to be able to fill the vacuum that will be created by
the Israeli military withdrawal, we have first to know the size of
this withdrawal and where it will go," he was quoted as saying by
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"UNIFIL is a peacekeeping force. Any change in its role or its
location must be contingent on the Lebanese government's
agreement," the spokesman reiterated.
</P>
<P>
About 400,000 of Palestinian refugees, driven out of their
homeland during decades of Arab-Israeli conflicts, live in camps in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
UNIFIL was founded in 1978 after Israel launched a large-scale
invasion to Lebanon. The 4,500-strong UNIFIL's term is renewed
every six months by the Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
