<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Health Minister Osama Abdel-Majid will
inaugurate the Saudi Medical Care Fair, said the Arabic daily Al-
Haiyat on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Riyadh Fair Corporation, the event runs for
five days with the participation of about 200 local and foreign
firms displaying the latest hospital equipment.
</P>
<P>
In line with the fair, Riyadh-based May Clinic will organize
lectures and discussions on such diseases as diabetes and
hepatitis, as well as on liver transplant.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunis and India have signed accords on bilateral
legal, agricultural and scientific research co-operation, the
Arabic daily Al-Haiyat quoted an official Tunisian source as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony took place at the conclusion of the Joint
Tunisian-Indian Joint Commission's 18th session in Tunis on
Thursday, said the report.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day session, the two sides also concluded a co-
operative pact between the Tunisian Industrial Federation and the
Indian Industrial Association as well as an accord on bilateral
cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Trade exchange volume between Tunisia and India in 1999 hit 225
million dinars (188 million U.S. dollars), mostly in Tunisia's
favour.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli radio on Thursday said a big offshore
natural gas field was verified in the Mediterranean waters by the
Israeli coast, adding that it is located off the coast of Askalan,
southern Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
In March, Israel announced that several gas fields were proven
in the same area.
</P>
<P>
Those fields can be commercialized as they can meet a 15-year
consumptive period with a reserve capacity of 45 billion cubic
meters.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The fourth Istanbul Garden Fair was opened in Turkey's
largest city of Istanbul on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 105 companies from some 20 countries are
participating in the fair, which will last until April 9.
</P>
<P>
On display are garden furniture, beach umbrellas, pool
equipments and chemicals, landscape and garden architecture, garden
tools, irrigation equipments and plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
