<HEADLINE> Australian Sharemarket Closes Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stockmarket closed
higher as News Corp and the technology sector bounced back into
favor.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries added 25.8 points to 3168.2.
</P>
<P>
The tone was set in New York overnight where the Nasdaq
composite closed 98.34 points higher at 4,267.56.
</P>
<P>
News Corp stormed back with a 1.111 Australian dollar rise to
22.946 Australian dollars. Kerry Packer's Publishing &AMP;
Broadcasting was not to be outdone, soaring 1.35 Australian
dollars to 13.65 Australian dollars, while rival Telecaster Seven
rose 19 cents to 7.40 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Telstra gained 14 cents to 7.67 Australian dollars. C&AMP;W Optus
advanced 15.5 cents to 6.30 Australian dollars and AAPT added 10
cents to 9.29 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications services provider SecureNet rocketed 2.65
cents to $2.45 Australian dollars. Other technology stocks were
also highly sought after being dumped this week. Open
Telecommunications jumped 1.15 Australian dollars to 12.05
Australian dollars, Melbourne IT regained 1.442 Australian dollars
to 11.442 Australian dollars, Keycorp surged 1.405 Australian
dollars to 14.30 Australian dollars. Solution 6 grabbed 33 cents
to 9.03 Australian dollars, Sausage rose 17 cents to 5.11
Australian dollars, Davnet climbed 10 cents to 4.54 Australian
dollars, ecorp bounced 18.6 cents to 4.53 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached 762.43 million shares traded for 1.56
billion Australian dollars (633.6 million U.S. dollars). Rises
beat falls 855 to 635 with 401 stocks closing steady. 
</P>
