<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Relaxes IPO, Mutual Fund Norms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Securities and Exchange
Board of India (SEBI) Friday liberalized public issue norms by
allowing companies to float a minimum of 10 percent shares to the
public through the initial public offerings (IPOs) from a minimum
of 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The SEBI also allowed mutual funds to invest in securities
backed by mortgages, paving the way for the funds to invest in
real-estate.
</P>
<P>
Currently, companies are allowed to issue a minimum of 25
percent of their equity capital in the primary market, except for
the information technology sector, where the limit is 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, mutual funds cannot invest in housing loan
securities as these securities are backed by mortgages and not by
assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
