<HEADLINE> Report Says South Korea Shows No Sign of Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 7 (Xinhua) -- No signs of inflationary pressure
have surfaced in South Korea, said a report issued by the Finance
and Economy Ministry Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the report on economic activities, the ministry said there
appears to be enough room left in the supply side with
manufacturing's capacity operation rate at 78.9 percent in
February, compared with 81 percent in the boom period of 1995 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
The business coinciding index in February this year edged down
0.1 percentage point while the leading index fell 2.3 percentage
points from the same period last year with no signs of inflation.
</P>
<P>
Economic recovery has been spreading to all industries,
including computers, semiconductors and automobiles, the three
major industrial sectors, with their production rising 18.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
The construction boom has also spread to the residential
housing construction from the public sector and consumer prices
rose 0.8 percent in the first quarter this year despite higher
international oil prices and school registration fees.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the current-account balance showed a surplus of 1.11
billion U.S. dollars in January and February and the establishment
of the new venture firms numbered 3,480 in February alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
