<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Mayor Chats with Citizens on Hotline (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Xu Kuangdi, mayor of this east
China metropolis, today chatted with citizens on a hotline opened
by the Shanghai People's Broadcast Station.
</P>
<P>
The "Mayor and Citizens" hotline is famous here, and it even
attracted Bill Clinton to visit it when the US president toured in
China in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue began at 12:00 am. The anchor first asked Xu to
explain his government's work to the audience. But Xu said he was
more eager to listen to what the citizens had to say.
</P>
<P>
The first call was from a Mr. Dong, who works for a private
company. Xu, 63, was the deputy dean of the Shanghai Metallurgy
Department in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Dong suggested that conventional industries should merge with
the IT sector.
</P>
<P>
Xu answered that the two sectors are very important, but there
is one problem: China cannot feed its 1.2 billion people with
virtual reality.
</P>
<P>
The second call came from a woman who had lived in the poor
western region for several years. She held that Shanghai, as a
prosperous city, must do something to help the west.
</P>
<P>
"I made steel in the west for one year, so I agree with you,"
said Xu, a metallurgist.
</P>
<P>
Xu is an academician of the Chinese Academy of Engineering. He
was elected the mayor of Shanghai in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Faced with a number of questions, including unemployment,
pollution and social security, Xu answered promptly and honestly.
</P>
<P>
A blind man named Chen complained that the official procedures
are too complicated for him to apply for setting up a private
company.
</P>
<P>
Xu told his secretary to write down Mr. Chen's address and
telephone number, and promised that the government would create a
much simpler and more direct channel for disabled people to run
businesses.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue lasted for 50 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
