<HEADLINE> Highlights of Diplomatic News Today (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are the highlights
of diplomatic news Xinhua released today.
</P>
<P>
China's WTO Entry Stressed
</P>
<P>
The Sino-U.S. agreement regarding China's accession to the
World Trade Organization (WTO) signed last year is in the
interests of both countries and will pave the way for China's
early accession to the WTO, which will contribute to a stable and
mutually beneficial relationship between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Shi Guangsheng and U.S. Commerce Secretary
William Daley today in a joint statement following the conclusion
of the 13th Session of the China-U.S. Joint Commission on Commerce
and Trade.
</P>
<P>
China stressed the critical importance of unconditional
permanent Normal Trade Relations (PNTR) in light of the China-U.S.
bilateral agreement on China's accession to the WTO, which is the
basis for the implementation of the bilateral agreement. The
United States stressed its commitment to work with the U.S.
Congress to obtain legal authority to grant PNTR, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
 U.S. Secretary of Commerce Pledges Efforts to Solve
PNTR
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of Commerce William Daley said here today that
the U.S. government is making great efforts to see that permanent
normal trade relations (PNTR) with China is passed by the U.S.
Congress.
</P>
<P>
"We are working very, very hard," he told reporters following
the conclusion of the 13th session of the Sino-U.S. Joint
Commission on Commerce and Trade.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that when the people see the benefit of PNTR,
then the Congress will pass it," he added.
</P>
<P>
The secretary said that U.S. President Bill Clinton is strongly
committed, and has spent a tremendous amount of time over the last
two and half months to get the Congress to pass PNTR.
</P>
<P>
There are now many activities going on in Washington, and the
president is meeting with almost 100 members of the House of
Representatives, he told reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
