<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Diplomatic News Today (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China and the United States began their first meeting on
commerce and trade here Friday since signing a bilateral agreement
on China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO) last
November.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of Commerce William Daley and Chinese Minister
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) Shi Guangsheng
co-chaired the 13th session of the China-U.S. Joint Commission on
Commerce and Trade.
</P>
<P>
A press release from MOFTEC said the meeting is of great
importance to the healthy and stable development of two-way
economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides agree that the U.S. unconditionally resolving the
permanent normal trade relations (PNTR) issue as soon as possible
is critical to the implementation of the bilateral (WTO) agreement,
" according to the press release.
</P>
<P>
During the hour-long session, the two sides also discussed a
number of issues ranging from China's strategy of developing its
vast western region and cooperation between small enterprises of
the two countries to the establishment of a regular consultation
mechanism, legal exchanges, and cooperation in other sectors.
</P>
<P>
 China Urges U.S., Britain to Cancel "No-Fly" Zone in
Iraq
</P>
<P>
China today urged the United States and Britain to cancel the "
no-fly" zone in Iraq and stop military actions against the country.
</P>
<P>
Chinese FM spokesman Sun Yuxi made the remarks when asked to
comment on the April 6 bombing by U.S. and British warplanes of
residential districts in Iraq's Al Basrah and other regions,
during which quite a number of civilians were injured.
</P>
<P>
"China is really concerned over the recent development in Iraq
and feels deeply uneasy for the civilian casualties caused by the
bombing," Sun said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China has consistently advocated and time and
again stated that Iraq's sovereignty, territorial integrity and
independence should be fully respected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Diplomatic News Today (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Vietnamese National Assembly Delegation headed by its
Chairman Nong Duc Manh left here this afternoon for Shenzhen city
in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Nong Duc Manh and his delegation arrived in Shanghai Thursday.
Chen Tiedi, chairman of the Shanghai Municipal People's Congress
Standing Committee, met with the Vietnamese guests Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
 CPPCC Vice-Chairman Meets Jordanian Guests
</P>
<P>
Zhu Guangya, vice-chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), met
with a delegation of the Jordan-China Friendship Association, here
today.
</P>
<P>
Global Poverty Reduction Unlikely to Achieve Summit Target,
UNDP Report
</P>
<P>
Many regions of the world are unlikely to reach this year's
poverty reduction target as set by the Social Summit of 1995, said
a United Nations Development Program (UNDP) report on world
poverty released here today.
</P>
<P>
The three indicators used by the UNDP to measure long-term
poverty, namely, adult illiteracy rates, child malnutrition rates,
and the percentage of people threatened with premature death, were
all supposed to be reduced by half between 1990 and 2000,
according to the 1995 Social Summit target.
</P>
<P>
But figures in the UNDP Poverty Report 2000 cast grave doubt on
these over-optimistic projections.
</P>
<P>
The illiteracy rate for people over 15 years of age in East
Asia and the Pacific Region dropped from 20 percent in 1990 to 16
percent in 1997, still a long way from the 10 percent target. In
South Asia, which had the highest adult illiteracy record of 54
percent in 1990, the figure had been reduced by only 5 percent by
1997.
</P>
<P>
UN Calls for Strategies to Reduce Global Poverty
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Poverty Report 2000 released here today
called for the adoption of a new global poverty-reducing strategy.
</P>
<P>
The strategy should feature more input of resources, and more
emphasis on reducing poverty. While ambitious global target has
been set, donor countries are reducing their aid and existing
poverty problems have not been given due attention.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that efficient management lacks links between
state-planned poverty-reducing work and the grassroots level.
</P>
</TEXT>
