<HEADLINE> 124,000 Filipino Youths, Handicapped People Get Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The employment facilitation
programs pushed by the Philippine government in 1999 placed some
124,000 youths and handicapped persons in various jobs nationwide,
the Department of Labor and Employment (DOLE) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The DOLE-led employment programs grew by 8.8 percent in 1999
from 114,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Labor Secretary Bienvenido Laguesma said in a report that 121,
300 of the beneficiaries were either students or dropouts, and 2,
700 were handicapped people.
</P>
<P>
Laguesma, however, noted in the report the small number of
handicapped people who benefit from the DOLE programs and stressed
the need to push the programs harder so they will reach more
disadvantaged people.
</P>
<P>
He directed DOLE offices to remind establishments that they are
entitled to tax breaks when they employ people with disabilities
under the country's law.
</P>
<P>
Laguesma said the DOLE's efforts to facilitate the employment
of disadvantaged people nationwide as well as the employment of
youths through various programs are part of the government's anti-
poverty thrusts. 
</P>
