<HEADLINE> China to Develop Own Advanced Nuclear Reactors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China will focus on developing
advanced nuclear reactors with its own intellectual property
rights rather than merely relying on foreign technologies,
according to Xu Guanhua, vice-minister of science and technology.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the reactors must be Chinese-made, and safe
and economical.
</P>
<P>
China has built nuclear power plants in Zhejiang, Guangdong and
Jiangsu provinces, but the main technologies were imported from
foreign countries, including France and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony celebrating China's breakthrough in
producing some core nuclear technologies here today, Xu revealed
that China has the ability to develop its own advanced reactors,
and the government will invest more in this endeavor.
</P>
<P>
The new achievements include a helium gas circulator, a high-
temperature gas-cooled reactor, and a control rod diver system,
which all passed government examinations today.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the high-temperature gas-cooled reactor is of
particular significance, because only the United States, Germany
and Japan were previously able to produce such reactors.
</P>
<P>
China is building its first such reactor in the suburbs of
Beijing, with an investment of 250 million yuan (about 30 million
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Most of the key equipment of the reactor is made here.
</P>
<P>
Currently, coal accounts for 75 percent of China's energy
consumption, creating serious environmental problems. Xu said that
China will readjust its energy structure in the 21st century by
exploring new energy sources such as nuclear and hydroelectric
power.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Yiren, vice-mayor of Shanghai, said that the city will
participate in international competition in the nuclear energy
field by offering products that meet international standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minor Planet Named After Chinese-American Physicist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Minor Planet No.3463 was discovered in 1978 by the Purple
Mountain Observatory under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS).
The observatory is located in this capital of east China's Jiangsu
Province.
</P>
<P>
Tien, a member of the US National Science Board and Chairman of
Hong Kong Chief Executive's Commission on Innovation and
Technology, is internationally recognized for his research on heat
transfer technology.
</P>
<P>
He has received many honors, including the Max Jakob Memorial
Award, the highest international honor in the field.
</P>
<P>
Tien and his wife, Jiangsu provincial leaders and CAS
academicians attended today's naming ceremony.
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony, Tian also gave a presentation on the
development of the global knowledge-based economy.
</P>
<P>
According to international convention, those who discover minor
planets and have them confirmed by the Minor Planet Center have
the right to name them.
</P>
<P>
The Purple Mountain Observatory has discovered 34 minor planets,
and named them after a number of famous Chinese and foreign
personages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
