<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO African Regional Director Calls for Safe Blood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- African Regional Director of World
Health Organization (WHO), Ebrahim Samba, urged every Africans to
start safe blood to save lives.
</P>
<P>
In a message read on his behalf at the rally held here Friday
to mark world health day falling on April 7, he said that to
attain the goal of safe blood "we need everyone's contribution and
a strong commitment on the part of our governments to the blood
safety initiative for Africa."
</P>
<P>
In 1994 the WHO Regional Committee for Africa passed a
resolution urging African countries to develop blood safety
policies, mobilize resources for the development of blood
transfusion service infrastructures and set goals and targets for
the attainment of HIV-free blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
Seven years after the regional resolution was adopted less than
50 percent of African countries have adopted a national blood
transfusion policy, and less than 30 percent of them have
implemented their policies, according to the regional director.
</P>
<P>
He said in view of this alarming situation, the WHO Regional
Office for Africa in Harare, Zimbabwe, decided 1998 to create a
blood safety program to coordinate all related activities by
providing support to countries in policy development and
implementation, staff training, quality management, development of
standard operative procedures and promotion of operational
research on blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
More recently the regional office have strengthen the capacity
of the National Blood Transfusion Service in Harare and the office
will give similar support to the National Blood Transfusion
Service in Abidjan, Cote D'ivoire, very soon and the two centers
will organize training courses for blood transfusion staff of all
WHO African member countries, said the message.
</P>
<P>
He called on every African countries to have a well organized
donor recruitment system and every Africans to be sensitized to
appreciate the meaning of the slogan: "safe blood starts with me".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
