<HEADLINE> War Hinders Angola's Tourism: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Angolan authorities of tourism
attributed here on Friday the actual tough situation of the
country's tourism to the troublesome civil conflicts between the
government troops and the rebels led by Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
According to Mario Justo, the Chief Supervisor of the Angolan
Hotel Department, the war is the main obstacle to tourism
development in the country, especially in the central highland
that includes the provinces of Huambo, Bie, Malange and parts of
Moxico.
</P>
<P>
Justo said that tourism in those areas has been seeing a
standstill since the recrudescence of the civil war in 1998, as
most of the main touristic areas are militarized.
</P>
<P>
"There is no tourism in Huambo because the great touristic
zones of the region are militarized", he said.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said that the Huambo province is famous for its
great scene of primitive parkland and the far flung thermal
regions.
</P>
<P>
He said the most famous touristic centers, thermal regions in
the districts of Lwama, Gove and Kuando dams as well as the "Ilhas
dos Amores (Love Islands)", have gone out of use due to the
political, military situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
