<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Might be Treated as Single Country, Says FIA Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Europe's long-standing monopoly in
hosting motor racing Grand Prix races seems on the way to end in
the near future as the sport's world governing body International
Automobile Federation (FIA) shall treat the European Union and its
member states as a single country.
</P>
<P>
In that way, EU could only host two grand prix a year in the
future, FIA president Max Mosley said in Imola, Italy on Friday.
No single country has hosted more than two world championship
races in a season.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in the Italian city, the FIA
chief said that the organization's world council had decided to so
propose to FIA's general assembly.
</P>
<P>
The council had reached that decision after discussing the
protracted dispute between the FIA and the EU competition watchdog
over the handling of television rights.
</P>
<P>
Eleven of this year's world championship races are set for
Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
