<HEADLINE> Survey: U.S. Companies Vow to Increase Investment in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A survey over 130 United States
companies in China conducted by the American Chamber of Commerce
in China (ACCC) shows that 88 percent of the companies will expand
their businesses in China.
</P>
<P>
The results of the survey were released recently in the year
2000 white paper of "American companies in China" by the ACCC.
</P>
<P>
There is prevailing optimism among U.S. investors toward the
Chinese market despite ups and downs in bilateral relations.
Direct investment from the U.S. increased by over 10 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
The white paper noted that for U.S. companies, a favorable
business environment means that they can operate in stable and
reliable conditions. And the most important element of business
environment lies in the legal system of industrial and commercial
management.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. companies hope that China will enter the World Trade
Organization as soon as possible. 
</P>
