<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Seek Greater South-South Cooperation at G-77 Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will seek greater
South-South cooperation at the summit of the Group of 77 to
strengthen the negotiating position of the G-77 in its dialogue
with the North, Foreign Minister Syed Hamid Albar said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad will lead the
Malaysian delegation to the Havana summit, scheduled for April 12-
17 and which China will attend for the first time, Syed Hamid told
a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
On China's participation, Syed Hamid said China is a big
country and it cannot be excluded following the emergence of a new
world order.
</P>
<P>
"I think the world needs to be a multipolar where all could
cooperate to make a more equitable world or else we see developing
countries on the receiving end," he said.
</P>
<P>
The summit will provide Malaysia with the opportunity to
exchange views on issues of common concern with other member
countries, he said, adding that Malaysia will also be able to
state its position on a number of international issues,
particularly on the reform of the international financial
architecture and globalization.
</P>
<P>
He said Mahathir will address the summit and raise, among other
issues, globalization and the technological advances.
</P>
<P>
According to Syed Hamid, the summit, to be preceded by a
meeting of senior officials on April 10 and that of foreign
ministers the next day, will address the issues of globalization,
North-South relations, South-South cooperation, knowledge and
technology.
</P>
<P>
The Havana summit is also expected to discuss preparations for
the 55th United Nations General Assembly and Summit of the
Millennium to be held in September, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
