<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls Show Fewer Danes Support EMU Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of people supporting
Denmark's entering the European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU)
has reduced considerably compared with earlier this year,
according to two opinion polls published Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a poll conducted by the Greens Analyse Institut among the
984 people questioned on the issue, 46 percent expressed support
for the EMU entry, while 42 percent were against it and 10 percent
said they are undecided.
</P>
<P>
Another poll carried out by the Vilstrup Research showed that
37 percent of 1,500 people were for the EMU entry, while 34
percent were against it and 26 percent still undecided.
</P>
<P>
The two polls were taken between April 2 and 5.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls conducted earlier this year showed that
supporters for the EMU entry accounted for 54 percent and there
were only 34 percent against it.
</P>
<P>
Danish Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen announced a month
ago that a referendum will be held on September 28 on the EMU
issue.
</P>
<P>
Denmark is one of the four European Union member states that
still stay out of the EMU. The other three are Great Britain,
Sweden and Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
