<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's National Health Service Plunging Deeper Into Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The National Health Service (NHS)
is facing a worsening of its financial crisis caused by a growing
number of patients complaining about ill-treatment, official
figures have confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Although the public was promised billions of pounds for new
hospitals, nurses and doctors, a latest report from the National
Audit Office shows that much of the cash will be spent instead in
the law courts.
</P>
<P>
The spiraling cost of clinical negligence cases could amount to
a total of 3.4 billion pounds (5.44 billion U.S. dollars) during
the past financial year if all incidents that occurred are
reported.
</P>
<P>
The cost for cases already dealt with increased by 600 million
pounds (960 million dollars) to 2.4 billion pounds (3.84 billion
dollars) but another 1 billion pounds (1.6 billion dollars) has
been allocated.
</P>
<P>
David Davis, Chairman of the House of Commons Committee of
public Accounts, said: "Funding successful claims for clinical
negligence means that there is less cash available to treat
patients."
</P>
<P>
The growing cost, partly due to patients' increased tendency to
sue over ill-treatment, will help to push the overall deficit of
the NHS from 18 million pounds (28.8 million dollars) to 200
million pounds (320 million dollars) next year, Davis added.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the National Audit Office also noted that the
growing financial difficulties of the NHS were mainly caused by
the record numbers of patients receiving treatment. However, he
added that under present conditions the deficit was "likely to
grow if anything." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
