<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Seed Upset in Japan Open Badminton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- World champion Peter Gade
Christensen was upset by unseeded Roslin Hashim of Malaysia,
failing to make the last four in the Japan Open badminton
tournament here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Hashin, who routed world silver medalist Fung Permadi of
Chinese Taipei and Sun Jun of China in the earlier stages,
continued his giant-killing run by beating defending champion
Christensen 16-17, 15-7, 17-14 in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Hashim was only ranked sixth in his country and 33rd in the
world, with a sole victory came in the Dutch Open in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In the semi-finals on Saturday, Hashim will take on third-
seeded Hendrawan of Indonesia, who ended Ahn Jae-Chang's seed-
killing run as the South Korean retired for an injury.
</P>
<P>
The other semi-final will be a re-match of the All-England semi-
finals between the eventual champion in Birmingham, Xia Xuanze of
China, and his compatriot Ji Xinpeng.
</P>
<P>
Second-seeded Xia, who won the Dutch and German Opens last
season, defeated fifth-seeded compatriot Luo Yigang 15-10, 15-2 in
an all-Chinese affair, while Ji narrowly beat Marleve Mainaky of
Indonesia 17-15, 8-15, 15-10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
