<HEADLINE> Sandstorms Set Off Environmental Alarm (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Sandstorms that swept much of
northern and eastern China in the past weeks have set off alarm of
deteriorating ecology in the western areas, said China's most
authoritative news weekly "Outlook".
</P>
<P>
Over the past month, Beijing has been hit by six dust or sand
storms. The worst of the storms descended upon the city yesterday,
blotting out the sun and turning the sky dusty yellow.
</P>
<P>
The dusty winds of forces up to 7-8 originated from the
Mongolian Plateau reduced visibility and caused a major delay of
flights at Capital Airport.
</P>
<P>
"Sandstorms set off again the environmental alarm bells in
China's west," declared a signed article from the April 10 issue
of "Outlook magazine" which will hit newsstands tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
During the past few weeks, gusty winds from the northwest moved
through much of the country, blowing dust and sands into the
capital and even down to the east provinces of Anhui and Shandong.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, the country's largest eastern industrial city,
experienced a rare muddy rain, which meteorologists blamed on
worsening ecological deterioration in the less developed northwest
region of the country.
</P>
<P>
"The nasty winds of dust and sands have again highlighted the
urgency of environmental protection in China's west".
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that over the past few decades,
desertification in the country has been deteriorating instead of
improving.
</P>
<P>
Before the 1980s, China's desertified land expanded at an
average rate of 1,560 square kilometers a year. The figure rose to
2,100 square kilometers a year in the 1980s and to 2,460 square
kilometers in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Goldbach's Conjecture: Mission Impossible for Amateurs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A scholar from the Chinese Academy
of Sciences (CAS) suggested today that amateurs stop trying to
crack the difficult mathematical enigma, Goldbach's Conjecture,
because it is far beyond their ability.
</P>
<P>
It needs not only a solid background of mathematical knowledge
and some super talent to solve the puzzle, but also study how
other scientists have tackle the problem, said Lu Zhujia, a
research professor with the Academy of Mathematics and Systems
Science attached to CAS.
</P>
<P>
An amateur mathematics researcher can hardly possess all the
qualities which are vital to crack the Goldbach's conjecture, Lu
added.
</P>
<P>
In March, a British publishing house, Faber, and an American
publishing house claimed that they will give one million US
dollars to the person who cracks Goldbach's Conjecture within two
years.
</P>
<P>
This has made the conjecture a hot issue among math experts
around the world and also among Chinese math lovers.
</P>
<P>
The conjecture was put forward by the Prussian mathematician
Christian Goldbach in 1742. It states that every even number
greater than 6 can be expressed as the sum of two primes.
</P>
<P>
Supercomputers found the conjecture true for every even number
up to some very large figure but no abstract proof, a mathematical
sleight-of-hand is available to prove that the conjecture is true
for every number up to infinity.
</P>
<P>
Chinese mathematician Chen Jingrun proved that every even
number is the sum of one prime, plus a number that is the product
of two primes. And "it is the best result so far," according to
Alan Baker, a Cambridge University professor and Fields medalist
</P>
<P>
"It is unlikely that we will get any further without a big
breakthrough. Unfortunately there is no such big idea on the
horizon," the Times magazine quoted Baker as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that his academy has been receiving large groups of
letters and visits concerning the Goldbach's Conjecture during the
past month. But many amateurs just cannot avoid making simple
mistakes in their "solutions."
</P>
<P>
He said that CAS will no longer accept letters and visits
concerning Goldbach's conjecture because their is simply no time
to identify mistakes from amateurs' solutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Judge Criticizes Low Efficiency of Court Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China's top judge Xiao Yang today
criticized low efficiency in court hearings and the enforcement of
court rulings now widespread in many local courts across the
country.
</P>
<P>
"A considerable number of courts have been found to over delay
settlement of lawsuits and fail to enforce court rulings in time,"
Xiao Yang, president of the Supreme People's Court, told a
national tele-conference today.
</P>
<P>
"Such delays are also a reflection of judicial injustice, which
is detrimental to society." Xiao Yang warned heads of provincial
level higher people's courts, noting that "the long-existing
problem is commonplace in people's courts."
</P>
<P>
He was also severely critical of local courts for providing
unrealistic statistics to the SPC.
</P>
<P>
Statistics presented to the SPC have shown that courts in China
settle almost all lawsuits according to law. Xiao said some courts
do not accept lawsuits or just do not register them at the end of
the year to increase their ratio of lawsuit settlement.
</P>
<P>
The over delayed enforcement of court rulings is largely the
result of local protectionism, Xiao Yang said.
</P>
<P>
Xiao pledged that the SPC is considering new measures to solve
the problem of delays in case settlements and the enforcement of
court orders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
