<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak instructed Thursday night
Interior Minister Natan Sharansky to order the workers in charge of
issuing passports back to work, so as not to prevent Israelis from
vacationing abroad during the Jewish Passover holidays.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions of civil service staffers in the past week, which
have stopped short of an outright strike, made it impossible for
Israelis who had left their passport arrangement for the last
minute to go abroad for the Passover.
</P>
<P>
Apparently, it was pressure from this irate group that finally
prompted the prime minister to act.
</P>
<P>
If such back-to-work orders are issued, they may also enable
thousands of tourists stranded at the borders to enter the country.
Those tourists, whose countries do not have diplomatic ties with
Israel, had come to Egypt or Jordan with the understanding that
they would receive Israeli visas at the border.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- The police Thursday recommended closing the criminal
investigation of President Ezer Weizman on suspicions of bribery
and breach of trust in connection with funds he received from
French millionaire Edouard Saroussi.
</P>
<P>
All charges against Weizman, according to police recommendation,
should be dropped. The investigators said there is insufficient
evidence to support charges of bribe-taking and tax-evasion.
</P>
<P>
Although they found enough evidence to sustain an indictment
against the president on fraud and breach of trust, they cannot
press such charges because the statute of limitations has expired.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- The opposition Likud legislator Yisrael Katz said Thursday
that if the president does not announce his resignation by the end
of the Knesset (parliament) break in Passover, he will continue the
impeachment procedures he launched when the investigation against
Weizman began.
</P>
<P>
According to the basic law on the presidency, the Knesset can
impeach a president for improper conduct.
</P>
<P>
To launch the impeachment process, at least 20 legislators must
submit a complaint to the Knesset House Committee. If 75 percent of
the committee's members vote in favor of the impeachment motion, it
is transferred to the Knesset plenum for a vote.
</P>
<P>
Support of no less than 90 legislators are needed in the 120-
member Knesset to impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- A large number of politicians from across the spectrum
suggested that Weizman, who had just be spared of criminal charges,
should step down.
</P>
<P>
One Israel whip Ophir Pines congratulated Weizman, but added
that while from a criminal point of view the president has been
cleared of wrongdoing, the public aspect of the police report is
serious and, without doubt, President Weizman would have difficulty
continuing his position.
</P>
<P>
Internal Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami said he was sure that
the president, who is citizen No.1, will take the right decisions
at the right time. He said he had confidence in the president's
judgement. Likud Knesset member Dan Naveh told Channel One
that Weizman symbolizes the state and the question cannot be
decided within a criminal aspect, but by moral and public values.
He thought the findings require the president to do a lot of soul
searching. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
