<HEADLINE> Uncontrolled Export of Scrap Iron Damages Romanian Metallurgy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The uncontrolled export of scrap
iron has greatly hurt Romania's metallurgy sector, which has been
declining in the last decade, the official Rompres news agency
reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"It is a crime" to destroy the stainless steel equipment in the
chemical and food industry and sell it for 60-70 U.S. dollars per
ton only to have the foreign partners sell it back to Romania in
the form of stainless steel for 400-500 dollars per ton, said
Aurel Radi, president of the Metarom National Trade-Union
Federation (MNTUF).
</P>
<P>
Although the Romanian iron and steel works are reporting
shortage of raw material, the scrap iron is still one of the major
items for export, with 750,000 tons annually, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Radi said that of the 24 ships in the country's only seaport of
Constanta that are loading, 14 ships are exporting scrap iron.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the MNTUF wrote a letter to Prime Minister
Mugur Isarescu to draw the government's attention to the country's
metallurgy industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
