<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Pilot Likely to Be Freed Without Trial: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- An Italian pilot detained by Jordan
on charges of violating its airspace could be released without
trial and get back his small, confiscated aircraft, the
semiofficial Jordan Times reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The pilot, identified as Claudio Castagna, was detained for
questioning Wednesday after his plane was intercepted by two
Jordanian fighter planes and forced to land down at Azraq airport,
80 kilometers east of Amman.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Information Saleh Qallab said whether to
allow him to leave the kingdom depends on the prosecutor`s
decision.
</P>
<P>
The pilot faced charges of violating Jordanian air space and
civil aviation laws, and his P68 plane was confiscated after
touching down.
</P>
<P>
The small, twin-engined plane, had shuttled between Amman and
Damascus on business missions before the incident. Chartered by
Italian businessman Nicola Grauso and other three international
activists to protest the crippling sanction against Iraq, the plane
deviated from its routine line on Monday after taking off from
Amman, and headed for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Aviation officials said it re-entered Jordanian airspace on
Wednesday without permission, apparently from Iraq, and was forced
to land at 01:00 p.m. (1400 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The pilot and his passengers was demonstrating defiance of an
international ban on flights into Iraq, and they were given a hero`
s welcome by Iraqi officials after the plane touched down at an
airport in Baghdad on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The pilot said he had flown his aircraft at a low altitude once
inside Iraq on Monday to avoid radar detection by U.S.-British
fighter planes, which were policing no-fly zones in Iraq imposed in
the wake of the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian officials are further investigating the motives of the
pilot and his passengers for the dramatic mission in and out of
Iraq, the first of its kind since U.S. and British forces imposed
no-fly zones in the south and north of Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
