<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Overcomes Political Hurdle for EU Accession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has overcome a political
hurdle in its European Union accession negotiations as it concluded
the talks on common and foreign security policy (CFSP) with the EU,
local media reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed in Brussels on Thursday to close the CFSP
chapter and three less problematic chapters: social and employment
policy, fisheries and company law, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The closure of the four chapters means Cyprus has provisionally
closed 15 of a total of 30 chapters. It also assuages the doubts
that the division of Cyprus could impede the island's accession
course.
</P>
<P>
The CFSP had been left open from a previous round after four EU
members -- Italy, Germany, Britain and France expressed concern
over the implications Cyprus' division could have on this chapter.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third in the wake
of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Thursday saw the opening of two new chapters: fiscal controls
and regional policy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after his meetings Thursday in Brussels,
Cyprus' chief negotiator on EU accession George Vassiliou said he
was very pleased with the outcome of the meetings and in general
with the country's accession course.
</P>
<P>
However, he urged that things must be speeded up, especially in
matters relating to the value added tax (VAT) which Cyprus must
align with the EU rate.
</P>
<P>
At present, VAT in Cyprus stands at 8 percent and it should
intensify efforts to bring VAT to the minimum 15 percent the EU
requires of the applicants.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for EU membership in 1990 and started substantive
accession negotiations with the EU in November 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
