<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Underscores Support for Private Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa has underscored the importance to support private investors
with vision and commitment to enhance the country's economy, media
here reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an interactive meeting with chief executive officers
of private enterprises organized by Tanzanian Ministry of Trade
and Industries here on Thursday, the president said Tanzania is
very willing to work with people who are concerned about their
cash flows as they are about the nation's tax flows.
</P>
<P>
The rate of economic growth, the attained lowest inflation rate
in over 30 years and the increased government revenues so far are
insufficient to have an impact on poverty, he said.
</P>
<P>
Four percent annual growth is only about half of the rate of
growth that could have an impact on poverty, Mkapa told the
meeting which he described as opportune for looking back upon his
four-and-half-year administration.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the economic reforms the country is undertaking
might be politically unsustainable if the measures taken could not
lead to a better life for the people.
</P>
<P>
"We want to work with good corporate citizens, contributing to
the welfare and social development of those communities in which
they operate," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the nation to identify and encourage growth of
private investors and pave the way for them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
