<HEADLINE> African Leaders to Meet in Nigeria on Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Fifty African heads of state and 10
heads of international and bilateral agencies are expected at the
African summit on roll-back-malaria scheduled for April 24 and 25
in Nigerian capital Abuja, the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN)
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Also expected at the summit are 12 health ministers from the
Organization of Economic Corporation and Development (OECD), and
the former Mozambican first lady and wife of South African
ex-president Nelson Mandela, reported NAN citing its own source
at the summit secretariat in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
"During the meeting, the heads of state will reflect on the
economic and social burden of malaria and commit themselves to
the strategies and targets for its reduction", the news agency
quoted an official with the secretariat as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The heads of state will also be urged to adopt a plan of
action based on the provisions of the declaration and commit
themselves to the implementation, monitoring and evaluation of
the plan of action", the official said.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state would also be expected to address the issue
of poverty alleviation through the reduction of the malaria
burden on african citizens, said NAN.
</P>
<P>
According to NAN, the roll-back-malaria initiative, launched in
October 1998 by the founding partners including Word Health
Organization, UNICEF, World Bank and United Nations Development
Program (UNDP), is designed to intensify the battle against
malaria control worldwide with special focus on Africa where the
disease is the number one killer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
