<HEADLINE> Russia Not to Introduce Direct Presidential Rule in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Moscow will not implement direct
presidential rule in the republic of Chechnya, Russian Deputy
Prime Minister Nikolai Koshman announced Friday after meeting with
President-elect Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
He said the representative office of the federal government in
Chechnya will be reformed with officials from many federal
agencies coming to help set up government bodies in the province.
</P>
<P>
He said that under Putin's instructions, proposals should be
drafted in 10-14 days on establishing Chechen government bodies.
</P>
<P>
Koshman said the elections of State Duma, lower house of the
Russian parliament, in Chechnya will be held very soon.
</P>
<P>
Elections of the Chechen leader will be possible "after 2001 or
may be even later," he said. 
