<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights of
the most important news Xinhua released over the past week from
March 31 to April 6.
</P>
<P>
March 31
</P>
<P>
-- China's youngest oil company, the China National Star
Petroleum Corp., merged with the China Petrochemical Corp, or
Sinopec, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
-- The Industrial and Commercial Bank of China granted a stock-
hypothecated loan of 13.68 million yuan to Guangfa Securities Co.
Ltd., with an outstanding term of six months.
</P>
<P>
-- China will continue to enforce a fishing ban in the South
China Sea, East Sea and Yellow Sea this summer, Vice-Minister of
Agriculture Wan Baorui said.
</P>
<P>
April 1
</P>
<P>
-- China's first emergency program to prevent oil spill
accidents in China's oceans went into effect today.
</P>
<P>
-- An exhibition on China's latest patented technologies opened
today at the Revolutionary Military Museum, Beijing.
</P>
<P>
-- Activities polluting marine environment and damaging marine
eco-system will be seriously punished in China according to the
revised law on marine environmental protection, which went into
effect today.
</P>
<P>
April 2
</P>
<P>
-- China is expected to levy a new tax to raise funds for
increased spending on social security.
</P>
<P>
-- Latest statistics show that the total foreign investment in
Beijing increased by 1.6 percent on a year-on-year basis in the
first two months of this year to hit 295 million U.S. dollars in
contractual value.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese universities will take in 120,000 students this year,
30 percent more than last year.
</P>
<P>
-- The first nuclear fuel element plant in China broke ground
in Baotou City in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region,
which is expected to provide fuel elements for a nuclear power
station in east China.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice Premier Qian Qichen urged that overseas
investors set up tourism agencies in China to attract more
visitors.
</P>
<P>
April 3
</P>
<P>
-- China has re-opened a cemetery for members of the Jewish
faith, prior to the traditional Tomb-sweeping Day, which falls on
April 4.
</P>
<P>
-- China's prestigious Beijing University and the Beijing
Medical University officially merged today. The new university
maintains the name Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese government issued a circular today banning
direct sales, which are staging a comeback in the country.
</P>
<P>
-- China, the world's largest textile and garment producer, now
turns out more than 20 billion garments a year, tantamount to
three garments for every person on Earth.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S.-based WI Harper Group said that it will raise funds
of more than 500 million U.S. dollars to invest in e-commerce and
Internet-related industries in Asian areas.
</P>
<P>
April 4
</P>
<P>
-- China will, as always, make efforts to develop its good-
neighborly and friendly relations with Viet Nam, Chinese top
legislator Li Peng said.
</P>
<P>
-- China has started to build the country's largest basic
geological information system with a group of data banks. The
system will be completed in 2008.
</P>
<P>
-- Stargazers in Beijing will be able to see three of the nine
planets -- Mars, Saturn and Jupiter -- near the moon on the
evening of April 6, according to the Beijing Astronomical
Observatory.
</P>
<P>
-- China is drafting a national action plan in a bid to clean
up its most polluted sea area -- the Bohai Sea in northern China --
within the next three decades, according to Wang Jirong, vice
director of China's State Environmental Protection Administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
