<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
April 5
</P>
<P>
-- Russian business people may cross the border into China at
Manzhouli, in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, and
do business for one day without needing visas. The new regulations
save the visitors about 40 percent of the time they normally used
to complete border-crossing procedures.
</P>
<P>
-- A special agent which can absorb and store water 500 or even
3,000 times the weight of a single seed can help to battle the
scourge of drought. The agent was developed by Prof. Wang Shuyu of
the Northeast Agricultural University in this capital of Liaoning
Province.
</P>
<P>
-- China now allows individual workers to buy and sell shares
of collective enterprises as the State Administration of Taxation
(SAT) asked individual workers owning such shares to pay income
tax today.
</P>
<P>
-- IBM signed an agreement today with the Xi'an Software
Industrial Park to create a world-class software platform in this
capital city of northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
-- China has called for strengthening the precautions against
the possible importation of infected birds and related products
from Italy.
</P>
<P>
-- China will import "dry-water", a U.S. patented irrigation
technology, this year for trial use in the afforestation of the
country's western region.
</P>
<P>
-- The 4th China International E-Commerce Summit opened today
in Beijing. The four-day meeting attracted more than 300
information technology multinational corporations and 100 industry
leaders from home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
April 6
</P>
<P>
-- Xinhua News Agency today released the full text of Vice
Premier Li Lanqing's speech on March 2 which called for the
improvement of education in an effort to let Chinese youngsters
grow up in a healthy way.
</P>
<P>
-- China is scheduled to offer a daily report on the quality of
the air in 41 major Chinese cities from June 5, this year.
</P>
<P>
-- Experts here expect significant nuclear power development in
China in the 21st century, with the country's nuclear power
generating capacity forecast at 20 million kilowatts by the year
2010.
</P>
<P>
-- China is speeding up development of the Shenfu-Dongsheng
Coalfield, the world's eighth largest, in northwestern China.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing will attend the South Summit
to be held in Havana from April 11 to 21 at the invitation of
President Olusegun Obasanjo of Nigeria, the host country of Group
77, and President Fidel Castro of the Council of State and the
Council of Ministers of Cuba, the host country of the South Summit.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin today urged the United States
to properly handle the issue of granting China permanent normal
trade relations.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice Premier Qian Qichen has called on the new leader of
Taiwan region to take substantial steps, instead of merely making
gestures, to win trust from others.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese senior high schools will use new Chinese textbooks
when school opens this September, shedding the current ones which
have been on the shelves for the past two decades.  
</P>
