<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imperial Railway To Become Tourist Attraction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 7 (Xinhua)-- An imperial railway once built
for the emperors and his relatives to visit their ancestors tombs
north of Beijing is being renovated for tourists.
</P>
<P>
The 42-km railway started from Gaobeidian stop in North China's
Hebei Province and ended at a Qing Dynasty hostel near the
imperial tombs.
</P>
<P>
The renovated railway will be ready to pick up tourists at the
Beijing West Railway Station on April 26. The train used on this
special railway consists of 14 Qing style carriages. It takes one
hour and 40 minutes to reach the tombs.
</P>
<P>
The railway was originally built in 1902, by over 10,000
workers in six months. The railway suffered severe damage during
the war against the Japanese invaders in the late 1930s and 1940s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
