<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Education News in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 China to Hold Children Calligraphy, Painting Contest
</P>
<P>
China will hold the fifth national calligraphy and painting
contest for middle and primary school students later this year,
according to the Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
With "The Motherland in My Heart" as the theme, the event is
aimed at enriching the extracurricular activities of students and
promoting art in schools.
</P>
<P>
New Chinese Textbook Stressing Culture Quality
</P>
<P>
Chinese senior high schools will use new Chinese textbooks
when school opens this September, shedding the current ones which
have been on the shelves for the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
Education experts here see adoption of new Chinese textbooks
as "an important part of Chinese teaching reform."
</P>
<P>
The new textbooks stress cultivation of students' cultural
understanding, aesthetic taste, and literature appreciation, with
a goal to improve the students' overall Chinese literature and
language skills.
</P>
<P>
Sophomores Becoming Teacher Aides, Student Counselors
</P>
<P>
Four sophomores have taken up teaching aide and student
counselor positions at the Hangzhou Business College from the
beginning of the spring semester. If they perform well, they will
be put in charge of a freshmen class, says an official from the
college.
</P>
<P>
China Inland Middle School to Enroll Xinjiang Students
</P>
<P>
Some twelve senior high schools in China's inland will enroll
students from the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in the new
semester which starts in September, said vice-minister of
Education Zhang Baoqing on April 6.
</P>
<P>
The move to give stronger support to Xinjiang in the field of
human resources development is a concrete step to implementing the
central government's strategy to develop the vast western part of
China, which includes Xinjiang, Zhang told a national high school
work conference on the enrollment of students from Xinjiang.
</P>
</TEXT>
