<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Chinese Cities Continue to Report Dusty Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dry weather, high-temperatures, a lack of vegetation in the
region, and strong winds were blamed for dusty weather resulting
in a drastic increase of suspended air-borne particles in the air
in northern China.
</P>
<P>
From March 31 to April 6, Hohhot, capital of the Inner
Mongolian Autonomous Region, north China, reported hazardous air
as it was hit by sandstorm originated from its west on April 3.
</P>
<P>
The cities of Tianjin, Taiyuan, Yinchuan and Urumqi reported
unhealthy air pollution. Beijing, Lanzhou, Shijiazhuang, Zhengzhou,
Xinin, Changchun, Xi'an, Harbin, Chongqing and Shenyang reported
slight air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three cities, mostly in southern China, such as
Guangzhou, Wuhan, Nanjing, Fuzhou, Chengdu and Guiyang enjoyed
fairly good air, while Zhanjiang, Shanghai, Haikou, Beihai, Zhuhai,
Shenzhen, Xiamen and Guilin reported excellent air.
</P>
<P>
Hohhot, Tianjin, Taiyuan and other 31 cities listed suspended
particles as the major pollutant. Sulfur dioxide was the major
pollutant in Chongqing, Changsha and Nantong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
