<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Export Values Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Figures released here Friday by
Statistics New Zealand show that New Zealand export values
recorded the strongest growth in the latest six-month period since
1992.
</P>
<P>
For the month of February this year, the provisional value of
New Zealand merchandise exports was 1.13 billion U.S. dollars
compared with 1.12 billion U.S. dollars for imports. It is rarely
seen that New Zealand trade balance for the month of February was
a surplus.
</P>
<P>
According to the government statistical department, the
provisional value of New Zealand merchandise exports for the year
from March 1999 to February 2000 was 12.1 billion U.S. dollars, up
eight percent from the previous year. This growth was assisted by
the low New Zealand dollar and strengthened commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
But the value of New Zealand merchandise imports rose by 16.4
percent over the same period to 13.77 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Australia, the United States and Japan continue to be New
Zealand's main export destinations. For the year from March 1999
to February 2000, the destinations contributing the most to the
annual growth in New Zealand exports were Australia, the United
States, Britain and the Republic of Korea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
