<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Picasso's Oil Painting on Display in Auckland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Pablo Picasso's oil painting,
Verre et pichet (glass and pitcher) was unveiled at the Simpson
Grierson Season launched by the Auckland Art Gallery Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Television New Zealand, it is the first
Picasso oil painting to enter a New Zealand public collection and
the first time this work has ever been shown in public.
</P>
<P>
Picasso painted Verre et pichet in 1944 during the Battle of
Paris. It is placed alongside works by other artists who make
personal or political statements about the experience and cruelty
of war.
</P>
<P>
The Simpson Grierson Season, which showcases New Zealand's
finest art collection, runs from April until October 2000. The
works it displays span 700 years of European art as well as
drawing on art from the United States, Australia and New Zealand (
including works by Maori and Pacific artists).
</P>
<P>
The Picasso oil painting Verre et pichet was recently acquired
by the Auckland Art Gallery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Z. Will Dump Monarch as Head of State: PM Clark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Helen Clark said here Friday that it's inevitable that New Zealand
will eventually dump the monarch as head of state.
</P>
<P>
She made the statement when she was addressing the Building A
Constitution conference organized by Wellington-based Victoria
University's Institute of Policy Studies.
</P>
<P>
But, the prime minister noted that there is no public mood at
the moment for the country to become a republic, "nor is it
anywhere near the top of my priorities."
</P>
<P>
Clark said that when she was a child people still referred to
Britain as "home."
</P>
<P>
"Now, at age 50, I wonder what the association means to
teenagers, 20- and 30-year-olds. I suspect not too much," she said.
</P>
<P>
A growing number of New Zealanders now have no connections with
Britain. "Will not those new New Zealanders not pose the question
why we retain as head of state a monarch who resides 12,000 miles
away?" she asked.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, Clark had said that a decision to
drop the Queen as head of state and turn New Zealand into a
republic has to be driven by the public, not the government. "It
is inevitable, however, that as New Zealand society changes, the
country would change to a republic," she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
