<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Crops Damaged by Cyclone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 30,000 hectares of
about-to-mature crops in the provinces of Matabeleland South,
Masvingo, Manicaland and Midlands of Zimbabwe have either been
completely swept away or flooded after the tropical cyclone Eline
hit the country a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
Crop production in the affected areas is expected to fall below
average, said the latest issue of the Southern African Development
Community food security bulletin released here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Current estimates put the total cost of flood damage to
infrastructure, crops, livestock and property in Zimbabwe at about
263 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains destroyed the little food stocks the rural
people had and affected 500,000 people, with 182,000 of them left
homeless.
</P>
<P>
Latest information indicates that as many as 100 people have
died in flood-related incidents. Most of the affected areas are
drought-prone where the food security situation is already of
concern at this time of the year. 
</P>
