<HEADLINE> Ugandan Court Issues Warrant to Arrest Cult Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A Ugandan court has issued a
warrant to arrest the leaders of the cult Movement for the
Restoration of Ten Commandments of God over charges of murder.
</P>
<P>
Buganda Road Court Chief Magistrate Andrew Bashaija said that
they must be brought to court to face the law on May 8, 2000, the
New Vision daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
State Prosecutor Michael Elubu applied for a warrant of arrest
follows an international one issued last month.
</P>
<P>
The cult founder Joseph Kibwetere and five others were held
responsible for murdering some 1,000 innocent followers in
Kanungu in southwestern Uganda and some other places used as
their residence or venue of activities.
</P>
<P>
On March 17, over 530 people were burnt to death in a church of
the cult in Kanungu and hundreds of bodies of murdered believers
were later exhumed from mass graves in other places. The cult
leaders, who are said to collect almost all the money belonging
to their believers, are still at large. 
</P>
