<HEADLINE> Cholera Alert Issued in Western Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government Thursday
night sent out a cholera alert in Nyanza and Western provinces,
both in western Kenya, after 24 people died of the disease in the
past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Friday quoted Ambrose
Moisore, Nyanza provincial health officer, as saying that at least
55 other patients had been admitted to hospitals by Thursday,
adding that about 250 others were treated and discharged in the
last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Pollution of Lake Victoria by industries and contamination of
local cities by direct raw sewage discharge can not rule out for
the outbreak of the disease, he said.
</P>
<P>
He advised local residents to boil their drinking water and
ensure that cleanliness in food preparation and handling is
improved, saying if they see any signs of diarrhoea, they should
seek immediate medical attention.
</P>
<P>
Medics in hospitals and medical institutions in the two
provinces have been put on alert to deal with emergencies.
</P>
<P>
Cholera was last reported in Nyanza in 1997 when it claimed at
least 1, 000 lives. The epidemic also spread in Western and Rift
Valley provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
