<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Girls Launch Campaign Against Child Sexual Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Girl Child Network
Thursday launched a one-year campaign in Chitungwiza near Harare
to fight rising child sexual abuse in the country.
</P>
<P>
The organization, with a membership of 1,500 girls, seeks to
sensitize the public on the need to give girls the same
opportunities as boys.
</P>
<P>
It also aims to raise public awareness on the psychological
effects of rape and invite members of the public to suggest ways
of dealing with the vice.
</P>
<P>
The girls, through this campaign, will be lobbying for the
reviewing of policy and laws that deal with forced marriages,
polygamy, the age of majority and inheritance.
</P>
<P>
The initiative came in the wake of reports that sexual abuse is
on the increase in the country, with children as young as three
months being abused by relatives.
</P>
<P>
Girls are also said to be engaging in sexual relationships when
they are as young as eight years old, increasing the risk of
contracting sexually transmitted illnesses, including the deadly
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
According to Project Coordinator of the Girl Child Network
Betty Makoni, 30 of their members were sexually abused, 50
suffered attempted rape and most of them physically abused.
</P>
<P>
The 12-month campaign would be characterized by workshops, art
 competition, conferences and camping, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the idea was to enable girls to access information on
opportunities, HIV/AIDS and their rights through defined channels,
such as clubs in schools, colleges and within the community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
