<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: DPRK, Japan Have Good Start for Normalization of Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Although the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) and Japan did not reach any agreement
here during the negotiations on April 5-7, the two countries have
made a good start toward normalization of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
According to the press statement released after the session
this morning, the talks were held in "a good environment," and "
the two sides have conducted sincere discussion on various issues
related to the realization of normalization of diplomatic
relations."
</P>
<P>
The two countries have also agreed to continue the talks for
the ties normalization and the next round of talks is expected to
open in late May in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
During the latest talks, Jong Thae-hwan, the DPRK's chief
negotiator, demanded Japan's apology and compensation for its
colonial rule of the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Japanese side, headed by Kojiro Takano,
reiterated Tokyo's main concerns including the so-called "missile
threat" from the DPRK and the whereabouts of "missing citizens" of
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Back in 1991, the DPRK and Japan began negotiations in
Pyongyang on the establishment of diplomatic ties, which ended
without any result after eight rounds of talks due to the wide gap
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral relations deteriorated in September, 1998, when
Japan imposed sanctions on the DPRK after the DPRK launched a man-
made satellite which Japan regarded as a missile test.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the two sides agreed to resume talks when a
Japanese delegation visited Pyongyang. Later, Japan lifted the
sanctions. All these have paved the way for the negotiations on
the normalization of relations between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
