<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Geologists Seek Water in NW China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China will invest 10 million yuan
(1.2 million U.S. dollars) in a project to look for underground
water and terrestrial heat resources in the Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region of northwest China.
</P>
<P>
A research group made up by geologists from the Chinese
Academy of Geological Sciences will investigate underground water
and terrestrial heat resources in the drought-ridden region.
</P>
<P>
The project's chief scientist is the well-known Chinese
geologist Zhang Zonghu, a member of both the Chinese Academy of
Sciences and the Chinese Academy of Engineering.
</P>
<P>
Scientists will also focus on the control of salinization and
desertification to improve the ecological environment of the
region.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the major problem restricting Ningxia's
development is the shortage of water, as the annual precipitation
in the region is less than 400 millimeter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
