<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Open Tobacco Auction Floors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's tobacco auction floors,
a main tobacco market in the world, are scheduled to open on April
26 amid threats by farmers to withhold the crop until the
Zimbabwean dollar devalues further, The Herald reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted General Manager of the Tobacco Industry
Marketing Board Stanley Mutepfa as saying on Thursday that the
opening would be on April 26.
</P>
<P>
There has been growing uncertainty surrounding the opening of
the floors,
</P>
<P>
with farmers indicating that they want the floors to open on May
3, expecting that the Zimbabwean dollar would have devalued by
then.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, the rate of the U.S. dollar to the Zimbabwean
dollar is one to 38. Farmers expect the rate to increase to one to
45 or even one to 78.
</P>
<P>
"If the exchange rate is favorable, then farmers would sell
their crop," said Director of the Zimbabwe Tobacco Association
Market Information Pat Davis. "In fact, farmers will be under a
lot of pressure to sell to off-set their debts."
</P>
<P>
Farmers are expected to sell 220 million kilograms of tobacco
this year, well above last season's 196 million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is the country's biggest foreign currency earner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African States Urged to Fight Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Southern African governments have
been urged to reduce the crime rate in the region in order to
attract potential investors, the Zambia Daily Mail newspaper
reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Robert Okello, director of the United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa, said at a press briefing in Lusaka on
Thursday that most of the countries in the Southern African region
are facing high rates in crime which affect investment.
</P>
<P>
"Governments should embark on ways on how to tackle high rates
of crime and then determine the solutions. The crime rate in the
region has been going up every year and it is having a negative
impact in many countries, hence we should fight it," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said potential investors in Southern African countries are
being discouraged from investing because of general insecurity.
</P>
<P>
"Governments should not only condemn high rates of crime as
people need to survive for them to live," he said, suggesting that
"employment systems should be revisited as a way of dealing with
reduction of high crime rates."
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
