<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Following are the cultural news
highlights released by Xinhua from March 31 to April 6:
</P>
<P>
Beijing to Break Ground for National Theater
</P>
<P>
China started on April 1 to construct the Grand National
Theater, which is expected to be completed in three years, after
two-year preparation.
</P>
<P>
The National Theater will be built just west of the Great Hall
of the People by Tian'anmen Square in central Beijing. Covering a
total area of 180,000 square meters, the National Theater will
include four major buildings -- an opera house, concert hall,
drama theater, and performance center, with a combined seating
capacity of 6,200.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier on Dragon Culture Studies
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen has called for further studies
of the country's traditional dragon culture.
</P>
<P>
This year is the Year of the Dragon on the Chinese lunar
calendar, and a cultural festival featuring the fabled creature
will take place in Dongfang city in south China's island province
of Hainan on April 6.
</P>
<P>
In his message to the upcoming festival, Qian said that it is
quite necessary this year to make further studies into the
spiritual connotations of traditional dragon culture.
</P>
<P>
World-Class Ballroom Dancers to Perform in China
</P>
<P>
The well-known Brigham Young University (BYU) Ballroom Dance
Company of the United States will be performing in China during a
May tour.
</P>
<P>
The dance troupe will also be seen in Guangzhou in Guangdong
Province, Nanjing in Jiangsu Province, Shanghai, and Xi'an in
Shaanxi Province, organizers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
