<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (1)  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights of
major environment stories Xinhua released during the past week:
</P>
<P>
China to Offer National Daily Report on Air Quality
</P>
<P>
China is scheduled to offer a daily report on the quality of
the air in 41 major Chinese cities from June 5, this year.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the State Environmental Protection Administration
of China (SEPA) said today the 41 cities include 31 provincial and
regional capitals, excluding Lhasa, capital of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, where the quality of the air is always
excellent, and 10 major coastal cities.
</P>
<P>
 Most Polluting Firms in China Up to Discharge Requirements
</P>
<P>
 Eighty-one percent of China's polluting firms had met the
official pollutant discharge requirements by the end of 1999, up
14 percentage points over six months previously.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Environmental Protection Administration,
the progress was made as local governments across China are trying
hard to make all of the country's 234,200 polluting firms meet the
requirements set by the central and local governments by the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Habitats of Giant Pandas Shrinking: Survey
</P>
<P>
Habitats of giant pandas in China are shrinking and
degenerating, latest surveys made by China's State Forestry
Administration (SFA) and the World Wildlife Fund (WWF) have shown.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted in Qingchuan County of southwest China's
Sichuan Province, the home to the rare black and white bear, found
that the habitat area was only two thirds of that a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
 China Drafting Action Plan to Clean Polluted Sea
</P>
<P>
China is drafting a national action plan in a bid to clean up
its most polluted sea area -- the Bohai Sea in northern China --
within the next three decades.
</P>
<P>
The State Environmental Protection Administration of China (
SEPA) is formulating the plan following a recent joint
investigation of the pollution in the Bohai sea by the central and
local government departments as well as the Chinese Navy.
</P>
<P>
Effective Afforestation Measures for West China
</P>
<P>
China's State Forestry Administration (SFA) decided Thursday to
publicize 100 effective ways to accomplish afforestation in the
country's western region to raise the survival rate of trees and
grass that have been planted.
</P>
<P>
Covering an area of 5.4 million square kilometers, the western
region is largely sandy and arid, where harsh natural conditions
make it difficult for newly planted trees and grass to survive.
</P>
<P>
To solve this problem, experts organized by the SFA came up
with 100 effective measures based on high technology and
successful experience in afforestation under similar conditions.
</P>
<P>
China's City of Springs Threatened By Water Crisis
</P>
<P>
Residents in Jinan in east China's Shandong Province, famous
for its many fountains, have been urged to stop using dripping
faucets starting this month to reduce the amount of wasted water,
as the city is being threatened by serious shortage of water
resources.
</P>
<P>
Local water supply officials said the underground water level
in Jinan is three meters lower than at the same time last year,
and what is worse, the water level is still dropping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Information Technology Forum to be Held in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A forum on information technology
(IT) will be held in Hong Kong on April 28 to discuss business
opportunities of the IT industry in both China's mainland and Hong
Kong after China joins the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the two-day forum will include government
officials, experts, scholars, representatives of corporations and
investors from the mainland and Hong Kong. The estimated number of
participants is about 400.
</P>
<P>
During the forum, a mainland and Hong Kong IT industry
roundtable summit meeting will be held.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Gaofeng, vice-president of the Chinese Academy of
Engineering, said that the total number of Chinese telephone users
reached 152 million by the end of 1999, and the figure for mobile
phone users exceeded 43 million.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 16 million computers users with 3.5 million
connected with the Internet, according to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
However, China's networks are still underdeveloped, said Zhu,
adding the there is a huge gap between urban and rural areas on
digital development.
</P>
<P>
The Forum is sponsored by the China Association for Science and
Technology and the Beijing-Hong Kong Academic Exchange Center and
has gained support from the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of
the State Council and the Liaison Office of the Central People's
Government in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
