<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A senior engineer with China's Central Meteorological
Observatory, said the dusty weather was caused by moderate gales
originating on the Mongolian Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia to Improve Ecology
</P>
<P>
China is to allocate over 20 billion yuan (about 2.4 billion U.
S. dollars) for some ten ecological projects in Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region in the first decade of the century.
</P>
<P>
The projects are expected to cover the whole region, and one of
them with an investment of 1.75 billion yuan is to build one
million hectares of forests in the 16 counties near Beijing to
deal with sandstorms.
</P>
<P>
Tigers Still Under Threat from Poaching and Trade
</P>
<P>
Despite a marked decline in the consumption of tiger-bones as
medicines in former tiger products consuming countries, there is
little evidence of a major reduction in the poaching of wild
tigers, according to a report released by World Wildlife Fund for
Nature (WWF) Tuesday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The report, titled "Far From A Cure: The Tiger Trade Revisited,
" revealed that the trade in tiger parts in traditional Asian
medicine continues to be a threat to wild tigers, with the trade
in some markets shifting to skins and other products besides bones.
</P>
<P>
China's Biggest Sewage Plant Up to ISO9002 Standards
</P>
<P>
The Gaobeidian Sewage Treatment Plant in eastern Beijing, the
largest of its kind in China, is up to the internationally
recognized quality control standard system ISO9002.
</P>
<P>
A recent appraisal has shown that the plant is up to the
ISO9002 standards, which can handle about 40 percent of the one
million tons of sewage discharged daily in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao Builds Air Pollution Monitoring Network
</P>
<P>
Qingdao, a coastal city in east China's Shandong Province, has
put into operation an automatic air pollution monitoring network
that covers all downtown and suburb areas.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring network covers all the seven districts and five
satellite cities of Qingdao. The city will use the computerized
network to monitor and release weekly reports about air quality
from June 5.  
</P>
</TEXT>
