<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Top Trade Officials Issue Joint Statement (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua)-- Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation Shi Guangsheng and visiting U.S. Commerce
Secretary William M. Daley here today issued a joint statement in
the wake of the conclusion of the 13th Session of the China-U.S.
Joint Commission on Commerce and Trade.
</P>
<P>
The full text of the joint statement reads as follows:
</P>
<P>
Joint Statement by the Chairs of the China-U.S. Joint
Commission on Commerce and Trade
</P>
<P>
Beijing, China
</P>
<P>
April 7, 2000
</P>
<P>
At the conclusion of the 13th Session of the China-U.S. Joint
Commission on Commerce and Trade, His Excellency Mr. Shi
Guangsheng, Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation of
the People's Republic of China, and His Excellency Mr. William M.
Daley, Secretary of Commerce of the United States of America,
affirmed the following:
</P>
<P>
The bilateral agreement reached between China and the United
States on November 15, 1999, regarding China's accession to the
World Trade Organization (WTO) is in the interests of both
countries and will pave the way for China's early accession to the
WTO, which will contribute to a stable and mutually beneficial
relationship between China and the United States. China stressed
the critical importance of unconditional permanent Normal Trade
Relations (PNTR) in light of the China-U.S. bilateral agreement on
China's accession to the WTO, which is the basis for the
implementation of the bilateral agreement. The United States
stressed its commitment to work with the U.S. Congress to obtain
legal authority to grant PNTR.
</P>
</TEXT>
