<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK, Japan End Talks Without Breakthrough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) and Japan ended talks in Pyongyang Friday without
any agreement but that they will meet again in Tokyo in late May.
</P>
<P>
The talks, aimed at normalizing diplomatic relations between
the two countries, were started on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement issued on Friday said the two sides
reconfirmed the need to continue the talks and agreed to resume
them in Tokyo in late May.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides, basing themselves on the understanding of the
need to improve and develop the DPRK-Japan relations, had sincere
discussions on all the matters related to the establishment of
diplomatic ties between the two countries, including a matter
related to how Japan will liquidate its past," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
In this round of talks, Pyongyang demanded a formal apology and
compensation from Japan over the atrocities inflicted on the
Korean people during Japan's occupation. Pyongyang also asked the
return of cultural treasures and the improvement of the legal
status of Korean nationals living in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The apology must be made by the head of the Japanese government
before the establishment of diplomatic relations, said Jong Thae
Hwa, who heads the DPRK delegation, at a press conference on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We must address the problems of the past as the top priority
or else we see no reasonable grounds for continuing the talks and
we will seek other ways."
</P>
<P>
The DPRK and Japan began their normalization talks in the late
1980s. Eight rounds of talks had been held before they were
suspended in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
