</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. gasoline prices should peak this month and
decline to an average of 1.46 U.S. dollars a gallon this summer
due to the impact of increase in worldwide crude oil production,
the Energy Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The latest analysis by the Energy Department's Energy
Information Administration (EIA) was in sharp contrast to its
forecast a month ago when the agency said that even with increased
oil production, gasoline prices were expected to soar to a
national average of 1.80 dollars a gallon.
</P>
<P>
But the estimated average price of 1.46 dollars per gallon was
still 25 percent higher than last summer's average of 1.17 dollars
per gallon.  (US-Gas Prices)
</P>
