<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newly Elected Japanese Premier Vows Efforts For "Rebirth of Japan" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Newly elected Japanese Prime
Minister Yoshiro Mori Friday pledged to achieve a "rebirth of
Japan" through such steps as economic recovery and educational
reform.
</P>
<P>
Mori, who took over Japan's premiership from stricken Keizo
Obuchi on Wednesday, said in his first policy speech to the Diet
or parliament that he plans to stay his predecessor's course.
</P>
<P>
"I will take over the policies of the former prime minister and
try to develop them further," Mori noted.
</P>
<P>
Mori said the policies he will maintain include Obuchi's
efforts to stir a genuine rebound in the economy and carry out
structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
"I will do my best to steer the economy onto a path toward real
recovery by enabling a smooth transfer from public demand to
private demand," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mori, a former education minister, said he shared Obuchi's
determination to reform the country's education system, adding
that he will have a newly launched panel draw up an interim report
around summer to promote the drive.
</P>
<P>
On Japan's foreign policy, Mori said he will continue efforts
to "ensure peace in Asia, especially Northeast Asia, based on
relations between Japan and the United States."
</P>
<P>
Mori, who is scheduled to meet Russian President-elect Vladimir
Putin later in the month, said Japan's policy of boosting ties
with Russia and concluding a peace treaty with the country has not
changed with the change of cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Mori also pledged to do all he can to ensure that July's summit
of the Group of Eight (G-8) major nations in Okinawa will be a
success.
</P>
<P>
Mori was sworn in as Japan's 55th prime minister late Wednesday
to take over from Obuchi, who remains in a coma after suffering a
stroke Sunday. Mori reappointed all of Obuchi's cabinet ministers
to ensure stability and continuity in government policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
