<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Rebels Involved in Trafficking Human Cargo: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's rebels of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) have been involved in a
massive racket in trafficking human cargo, said an official report
published here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's law enforcement authorities have uncovered that the
head of the LTTE finance division, R. Visendrarajan and his family
had sent 17,000 people abroad to 11 countries last year alone and
charged enormous fees on forged passports, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Most of these people who had been smuggled abroad are
reportedly languishing in detention camps in these countries.
</P>
<P>
Investigations have revealed that they have earned 25,000
million rupees (340 million U.S. dollars) last year from the
illegal operation assisted by six companies owned by Visendrarajan.
</P>
<P>
Visendrarajan also owns two shipping companies with six ships
used for gun running and shipment of armaments for the LTTE. Two
of Visendrarajan's abettors Wahid and Illiyas were allegedly
arrested last week.
</P>
<P>
They had also allegedly defrauded the department of Inland
Revenue to the tune of 22 million rupees (299,320 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"This operation is considered one of the LTTE's major fund
raising devises for its ongoing war with Sri Lankan government
troops," the report said
</P>
<P>
The war has induced several Sri Lankans to seek refuge abroad,
mainly for economic reasons.
</P>
<P>
It has been recently uncovered that the LTTE, which has been
fighting the war since 1983 for a separate Tamil state in the
country, is one of the largest ship owners in the world and its
ships are used for several illegal purposes, including gun running,
drug smuggling and trafficking in human cargo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
