<HEADLINE> Australian Protesters Storm Tree-planting Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of angry protesters
Friday stormed a tree-planting ceremony attended by Prime Minister
John Howard in the Blue Mountains west Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The protesters, wielding banners and screaming chants against
racism, shouted "Justice Yes, Racism No" and "Mandatory
Sentencing Has to Go."
</P>
<P>
Police were forced to form a barricade to prevent the
protesters getting close to the ceremony. A protester was
arrested whilst trying to force his way through the police
barricade.
</P>
<P>
The protest followed Aboriginal Affairs Minister John Herron's
denial of the existence of the stolen generation contained in his
April 2 report to the senate.
</P>
<P>
About 100 years ago, "half-caste" children were separated
forcibly by the then missionaries and government agents to
assimilate them and those "full-blood" aboriginals were left to
die out. The separated children are the so-called "stolen
generation."
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard Thursday apologized to
the aborigines hurt by the government's denial that the stolen
generation existed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
