<HEADLINE> Ukraine Protests Council of Europe's Intervention in Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine protested on Thursday against
the Council of Europe's attempt to postpone its planned referendum,
scheduled for April 16, denouncing it as unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Europe, a Europe-wide consultative assembly on
human rights and democracy issues, passed a resolution on Tuesday
demanding that Ukraine should put off the referendum until a new
law on referendums has been passed, and threatening to suspend
Ukraine's membership of the organization if President Leonid
Kuchma does not back down.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the Ukrainian Foreign Ministry said that the
resolution does not reflect the true reality of Ukraine,
criticizing it as "a contempt of the Ukrainian people,
constitution and legislation," and an intrusion of the ruling by
the country's constitutional court.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that no international organizations are entitled to
restrict the Ukrainian people's rights and freedom that the
country's constitution gives them to participate in the management
of national affairs.
</P>
<P>
It noted that holding referendums is "an important stage of
developing and improving democracy" in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Council of Europe's threat, Kuchma pledged on
Thursday to press ahead with a modified referendum after the
constitutional court ruled that two of the six questions were
illegal.
</P>
<P>
Voters will now be called on to vote on the four remaining
questions, which are the dissolution of parliament if it fails to
produce a governing majority within a month, the abolition of
parliamentary immunity, the reduction of the number of deputies
from 450 to 300, and the creation of an upper house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
In the end, the statement said that as a member of the Council
of Europe, Ukraine will continue its effective cooperation with
the 41-nation organization, although the council's "proposal is
not constructive."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
