<HEADLINE> Hungary's Economy Grows 4.45 Percent in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Hungary's gross domestic product
(GDP) grew 4.45 percent in 1999, keeping the record growth of over
4 percent for three years in a row.
</P>
<P>
According to latest data from the Central Bureau of Statistics,
GDP growth accelerated quarter by quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
The rate, which was 3.5 percent in the first quarter, rose to 3.
9 percent in the second, then to 4.5 percent in the third and hit
a record 5.9 percent in the last three months.
</P>
<P>
The economy has now regained the level of 1989, when the
Eastern European country underwent drastic political changes, said
Economics Minister Matolcsy Gyorgy.
</P>
<P>
Hungary's economy has maintained a steady trend of growth since
1994, with GDP growth registered at 4.6 percent in 1997 and 5.1
percent in 1998 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed growth mainly to increases in industrial
output, exports, as well in domestic demand and consumption.
</P>
</TEXT>
