<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pets Less Popular in Major Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- More than half of urban residents
are against owning a pet, according to a recent survey reported by
China Daily today.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the Bejing-headquartered Horizon
Investigation Company, interviewed 4,509 urban residents in eight
major cities including Beijing, Shanghai, Chengdu of southwest
China's Sichuan Province and Xi'an in northwest China's Shaanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
Only around 30 percent of the interviewees said they used to
own a pet, or would like to in the future.
</P>
<P>
Among those surveyed, dogs were ranked as the most favorable
pet with 54.4 percent of them saying they prefer to have a dog.
</P>
<P>
Taking a close second were cats with nearly 40 percent followed
by fish, birds, tortoises, rabbits and chickens.
</P>
<P>
Only 20 percent of those who used to raise pets said they had
unpleasant experience, while nearly 70 percent who have yet to own
a pet, said they are strongly dislike the idea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
