<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Says Permanent Peace Accord With Palestine Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Justice Minister Yossi
Beilin said here Thursday that it is possible for Israel and its
arch rival Palestine to conclude negotiations and reach a
permanent peace agreement by September 13 as stipulated by an
earlier peace accord.
</P>
<P>
On his visit to Portugal, which holds the European Union's
rotating presidency, Beilin told reporters that Israel and
Palestine have yet to settle a number of thorny issues through
negotiations, but these stumbling blocks are not insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
Under the Sharm El-sheikh Memorandum signed in 1999, Israel and
Palestine should reach a framework agreement on the final status
of Palestine by February 13 this year and sign a permanent peace
accord by September 13. But the two sides failed to meet the
February 13 deadline and agreed to set the end of May as the new
date.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli minister, who arrived here Thursday morning for a
one-day visit, also expressed regret at the break-down of Israeli-
Syrian peace talks. Israel and Syria suspended talks in January
after failing to eliminate differences on Israeli troop withdrawal
from the occupied Golan Heights in southwest Syria.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Beilin met Portuguese Prime Minister
Antonio Guterres and briefed him on the latest developments of the
Mid-east peace process.
</P>
<P>
Beilin also held talks with his Portuguese counterpart, Antonio
Costa, on developing cooperation between Israel and the EU in the
judicial field, and on strengthening exchange and cooperation
between the judicial sectors of Israel and Portugal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
