<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Asks U.S. Congress to Pass PNTR for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive
of China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR),
Thursday expressed his hope that the U.S. Congress will pass the
legislation for China's permanent normal trade relations (PNTR)
status.
</P>
<P>
"I certainly hope the House (of Representatives) will come to
the right decision," Tung told reporters at the lawn outside the
Capitol Hill building after meeting 7 senators and 16 congressmen.
</P>
<P>
The House will vote on the legislation in the week of May 22.
</P>
<P>
During the meetings, Tung briefed the legislators about the
development in Hong Kong after China resumed the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of my visit is really to be able to tell our
friends on Capitol Hill how well in the last two and half years '
one country, two systems' is being successfully implemented and
how well Hong Kong has recovered from the impact of the financial
turmoil," said Tung.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the main purpose of his visit is to explain to
senators and congressmen the importance of the PNTR legislation.
</P>
<P>
"It is of course very important to Hong Kong that the
legislation is passed, it's important to China. But it is very
important to the United States of America too."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress has annually decided after a debate to resume
the normal trade relations with China. The Clinton administration
agreed to grant PNTR to China when the two countries signed an
agreement last year on China's accession to the World Trade
Organization. The White House decision needs Congress approval.
</P>
<P>
Tung arrived in Washington early Thursday from New York and is
expected to have a private meeting with President Bill Clinton and
other senior U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
This is Tung's second visit to the United States since he was
elected chief executive of the HKSAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
