<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Televise Siberian Tigresses Giving Birth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A Siberian tiger park in northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province has decided to televise live the
birth of tiger cubs, park officials announced.
</P>
<P>
The Heilongjiang Siberian Tiger Park has invested over 800,000
yuan (about 96,380 U.S. dollars) to install more than 30 micro-
cameras in dens of expectant tigresses so as to televise the
process of the delivery of their cubs.
</P>
<P>
The move is to help visitors learn more about the rare animals
and to raise people's awareness of the importance of saving them
from extinction, Zhang Chengzhong, director of the park's general
managing office, said.
</P>
<P>
Siberian tiger mothers are vulnerable to difficult labor if
bothered by outside elements, especially people, when giving birth.
</P>
<P>
But people watching the process through television will cause
no harm to them, he noted, adding that every year four to five
tigresses give births to cubs in the park.
</P>
<P>
The park, which has over 60 Siberian tigers in captivity, is
the country's largest feline animal breeding center. It receives
about 200,000 Chinese and overseas visitors every year.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that there are now fewer than 300 wild Siberian
tigers in the world. China has about 10 such tigers living in the
wild.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
