<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Has On-Line Pager Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Pager users in this capital of
southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region now can read e-mail with
their pagers, following the opening of the website: http://pec.263.
net.
</P>
<P>
The online pager service was introduced to Lhasa by the Tibetan
Youxun Paging Station.
</P>
<P>
The number of Internet users in Tibet has surged from 300 at
the end of 1999 to the present 1,500, providing a basis for the
opening of the online pager service which transforms e-mail into
wireless signals that can be received by pagers. Users can enjoy
this service by applying to paging stations for e-mail boxes.
</P>
<P>
Online pagers, originally developed in the United States, were
introduced to China by Internet service providers and paging
stations a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
Online paging brings a new opportunity for the development of
Chinese paging stations, which have been competing with mobile
telephone services.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the country has 1,763 paging stations now,
with the number of pager users totaling 72.68 million.
</P>
<P>
Now, 50 paging stations in 21 Chinese cities including Beijing,
Shanghai, Xi'an, and Harbin, offer online paging service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
