<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Satellite Launch Provider Upbeat About Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- After successfully putting more
than 20 commercial satellites in orbit, China is considered a
launch provider with competitive ability, said Zhang Xinxia,
president of the China Great Wall Industrial Corp (CGWIC).
</P>
<P>
Exactly 10 years ago, China cautiously launched its first
international commercial satellite-Hughes Corp's Asiast I,
according to a China Daily report today.
</P>
<P>
Zhang's firm is the nation's only company authorized to provide
commercial launch service and work with foreign aerospace firms.
</P>
<P>
"Following its first success in 1990, China has carried out 24
commercial launches for overseas customers, placing 26 foreign-
manufactured satellites in space," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Satellites sent into orbit by CGWIC's Long March series of
rockets, 60 percent of which are commercial launches, service more
than 100 countries and are able to provide satellite
communications for three quarters of the world's population, Zhang
said.
</P>
<P>
To compete with international launch providers, China has
improved its carrier-rocket technology and increased the launch
capacity of its rockets.
</P>
<P>
The Long March rockets are now capable of carrying 5.3 tons of
payload into geostationary transfer orbit and 9.2 tons of payload
into low earth orbit, which means China is well able to send all
kinds of satellites into space.
</P>
<P>
China has grabbed 7 to 9 percent of the world's commercial
satellite launch market, said the president.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledges that China's aerospace industry suffered a
major setback in February 1996 with the unsuccessful maiden flight
of the Long March 3B. But the 18 following consecutive successful
launches have bolstered international confidence in the
reliability of the Long March rockets.
</P>
<P>
Zhang expected that his corporation will serve as an in-orbit
delivery supplier by sending Chinese-made satellites atop Chinese
carriers into the preset orbits for overseas users and provide
after-launch services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
