<HEADLINE> Ningbo Promotes Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Ningbo, a major port city in east
China's Zhejiang Province and the famous ancestral home of many
overseas Chinese living in more than 50 foreign countries, plans
to stage a series of tourism activities this year.
</P>
<P>
The activities will include a seafood festival, a mountain
climbing festival, a waxberry festival, and a celebration to mark
the 1,700th anniversary of the Tiantong Temple.
</P>
<P>
New tour routes to Mt. Putuo, one of the four mountains sacred
to Buddhists in China, the Emperor Asoka Temple, the Hemudu
Cultural Site, and other places of historic interest and scenic
beauty will be opened to both domestic and overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
Ningbo's scenic spots also include Tianyige, China's oldest
private library.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the coastal city hosted more than 11 million
tourists, including 112,000 from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Ningbo now has an international airport and 27 tourist hotels.
</P>
