<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Without Borders to Head for Tibet Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Doctors Without Borders, the
international medical relief group which won the 1999 Nobel Peace
prize, will soon go to Qamdo Prefecture in eastern Tibet to
continue its medical work.
</P>
<P>
According to Xavier Crombe, head of the group's Lhasa office,
the doctors will treat sufferers from Kaschin-Beck disease (
osteoarthrosis deformans endemica), train local medical personnel
and do research on the cause of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Doctors Without Borders, or Medecins sans Frontieres, was
founded in Paris in 1971 by a small group of French doctors. It
started working in Tibet in 1991, and has treated many Tibetan
patients since then.
</P>
<P>
Doctor Crombe said about three million people in the world are
suffering from Kaschin-Beck disease, most of them living in Asia
and some 10,000 in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
So far, the cause of the disease remains unknown, he said,
adding that some experts hold that some kind of fungus contained
in highland barley, a staple food on the plateau, and iodine-
short water are responsible for the disease.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
