<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School Building Quality Stressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Education has
vowed to ensure the safety of students by asking authorities to
eliminate dilapidated buildings from schools, China Daily reported
today.
</P>
<P>
"Every level of government should stick to related education
law and policies, take firm responsibility, pour more money and
labor, and do stricter inspections to prevent any further fatal
school-building accidents," Guo Zhenyou, director of the ministry
's supervision office, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
A few days ago, six students were killed at a village primary
school in east China's Jiangsu Province. The students died when
high winds knocked down a school wall on March 27.
</P>
<P>
Also last month, four students died in a dining-room collapse
in southwest province of Sichuan. The accidents have set off an
alarm about the deteriorating condition of China's school
buildings.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 13 million square meters of school buildings are
classified as "dangerous". The figure is less than one percent of
the total school building floor space of the country.
</P>
<P>
Though the proportion of dilapidated school buildings is small
and decreasing every year, the problem is still very grave, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
Guo blamed fund shortages, negligence and corruption for
rundown schools.
</P>
<P>
"The ministry has called for an overall inspection of school
buildings nationwide," the official noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
