<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kells Quits as Olympic Commissioner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Morley Kells, Olympic commissioner
in Ontario, Canada, has resigned amid delicate negotiations
involving the 2008 Games.
</P>
<P>
"I can confirm he has resigned," said Hillary Stauth, a
spokeswoman for Premier Mike Harris of Ontario.
</P>
<P>
The duty of the Olympic commission will be assumed by the
SuperBuild Corp, the provincial agency that oversees
infrastructure spending.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Kells made the recommendations that responsibilities for
the Olympics and waterfront development be shifted to SuperBuild
Corp., and so this is being done at his recommendation," announced
Harris' another aide Pierre Leduc.
</P>
<P>
According to local media, Kells felt frustrated over the budget
issue in negotiations between the city of Toronto, the bid
committee working on Toronto's proposal for the 2008 Games and the
province of Ontario, which insists on a guarantee that the
proposal won't run over budget.
</P>
<P>
He was unhappy with a lack of cooperation of officials from
Toronto city hall and the Olympic bid committee, who preferred to
deal directly with the premier's office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
