<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian FM Meets U.N. Envoy on Israeli Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign
Minister Faruk Shareh met here Friday evening with
U.N. chief's personal envoy Terje Roed Larsen on a
planned Israeli troops withdrawal from south
Lebanon by July.
</P>
<P>
Larsen, who arrived here earlier in the day
from Beirut, conveyed to Shareh a message from U.
N. Secretary General Kofi Annan on his talks with
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy in Geneva on
Tuesday, the Syrian Arab News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Annan, Levy assured
Annan that his country is determined to implement
the U.N. Resolution 425 which calls on Israel to
withdraw its army unconditionally from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was adopted by the Security
Council in 1978 after Israel invaded southern
Lebanon allegedly to wipe out Palestinian
guerrillas who had launched attacks on northern
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Levy also pledged that Israel will cooperate
with the 4,500-strong U.N. peacekeeping forces
stationed in south Lebanon during the July
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure of increasing guerrilla
attacks on Israeli forces in south Lebanon, which
resulted in seven deaths since the beginning of
this year, the Israeli cabinet earlier last month
approved Prime Minister Ehud Barak's plan to pull
out from south Lebanon by July with or without a
peace agreement with Syria, the main power broker
in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Larsen said his meeting with
Shareh was held in a friendly and cordial
atmosphere, adding that he and Sharek will keep in
contact with each other to advance the peace
process in the days to come.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shareh said his country understands
Lebanon's security concerns due to Israel's 22-
year-long occupation of the country.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials have threatened harsh
retaliation against Lebanon if its guerrillas
stage attacks on northern Israeli towns after the
pullout.
</P>
<P>
"Syria cannot but welcome full and
unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south
Lebanon," Shareh said, adding that he deems the
move as a "significant gain for Lebanon and the
Arabs as a whole."
</P>
<P>
No matter whether the withdrawal is genuine or
not, Syria will not yield to any pressures
whatever their sources might be, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Syria will never give up any of its rights to
land and water," Shareh stressed.
</P>
<P>
Israel has accused Syria of using Lebanese
guerrilla attacks on
Israeli forces in south Lebanon as a bargaining
chip to take back the whole Golan Heights, which
Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East
war.
</P>
<P>
Syria will continue urging the international
community especially the U.N. Security Council to
implement relevant U.N. resolutions on ending the
decades-old Arab-Israeli conflict so as to
establish a fair, permanent and comprehensive
peace in the Middle East, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which deploys about 30,000
troops in Lebanon, have insisted on the
integration of their talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Friday Shareh phoned Lebanese Prime
Minister Salim Hoss on the forthcoming Israeli
pullout and the obstacles set by Israel on the
road to peace.
</P>
<P>
Larsen discussed with Lebanese leaders on the
Israeli withdrawal before coming here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
