<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Parties Urged to Stop Fighting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Expressing its deep concern at the reports that the Islamic
faction of Taliban and the opposition United Front are preparing
for renewed large-scale fighting, the council condemned the
Taliban for the launching of new offensives.
</P>
<P>
"There is no military solution to the conflict and only a
negotiated political settlement aimed at the establishment of a
broad-based multiethnic and fully representative government
acceptable to all Afghans can lead to peace and national
reconciliation", the council said in a presidential statement
after an open debate on Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The conflict has entered into its 22nd year without any
tangible hope for a solution in the foreseeable future, according
to U.N. official John Renninger.
</P>
<P>
Countries in the region and beyond already suffer from the
spill-over of many Afghan-based problems including the flood of
refugees, narcotics, arms smuggling and cross-border terrorist
activities.
</P>
<P>
Continuous clashed between the warring factions took place in
various places throughout the winter with the front lines
remaining almost unchanged, Renninger told the council.
</P>
<P>
Renninger, Officer-in-Charge of Asia and the Pacific Division
in the U.N. Department of Political Affairs, said during the OIC-
sponsored talks involving the Taliban and the United Front in
Jeddah, Saudi Arabia from 7 to 9 March, neither side changed its
basic position.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban insisted that the opposition join the "Islamic
Empire", while the United Front reiterated that an interim
government including third parties should be established.
</P>
<P>
The OIC, or Organization of Islamic Conference, is attempting
soon to arrange further talks between the two sides in Jeddah and
the U.N. "fully supports this effort", said Renninger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Not to Take Part in CDU Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The conservative German opposite
Christian Democratic Union (CDU) will hold its first national
congress without Helmut Kohl in 30 years, Kohl's Berlin office
said.
</P>
<P>
The CDU congress, scheduled for next Monday in Essen city in
Ruhr industrial region, will elect Angela Merkel and Ruprecht
Polenz its leading duo, and the acting party chief Wolfgang
Schaeuble is expected to step down.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, the former CDU chancellor who is facing a criminal probe
for his slush funds scandal, in an open message thanked Schaeuble
and Merkel for their congratulations letter on his 70th birthday.
</P>
<P>
"I had tried to fulfill my duty. I am very glad to know that
many were successful, yet some were not so successful," said the
message.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's office added the former chancellor, who had led the CDU
for 25 years, would not take part in the party congress.
</P>
<P>
Again, Kohl in his message thanked his "personal friends" for
their "important support" to his work.
</P>
<P>
"My career in this decade was only possible because many had
support it. I am lucky that I have found many personal friends in
our society these years. I also thank them for their important
support to my work," said the message.
</P>
<P>
Schaeuble and Merkel sent a congratulatory letter to Kohl this
Monday for his 70th birthday. The letter, while eulogizing Kohl's
contribution to German reunification in 1990, also accused his
illegal funding practice.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, who has by now refused to disclose the name of his
benefactors for his "promise to personal friends," passed his
birthday quietly in an Austrian town, canceling all public
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian Presidential Candidates Close Campaigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian presidential candidates
Friday closed their electoral campaigns with mass rallies previous
to Sunday's general elections.
</P>
<P>
President Alberto Fujimori, who is bidding for a third mandate,
called more than 100,000 followers in the closing of his campaign
in Lima downtown Plaza Grau.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori, who leads in the polls with more than 40 percent of
the voting preferences, called on electors to avoid returning to
the past, to consolidate the reforms started by his government,
and made a series of promises if he is reelected.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian president has not been able to solve the serious
unemployment problem, despite achievements in the economic,
security aspects, and in the war against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
 Fujimori faces eight opponents. Only one candidate, Alejandro
Toledo, is considered a serious threat. A runoff would be
scheduled in late May or early June if no candidate achieves a
majority.
</P>
<P>
 Alejandro Toledo, the Peru Possible movement presidential
candidate, who has 30.2 percent of the Peruvian electors
preferences in the polls, closed his political campaign in the
Andean city of Cusco.
</P>
<P>
Toledo, an economy Harvard graduate, of humble origin and
without much political experience, has had a meteoric ascension
which makes him a serious prospect for the Peruvian presidency.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, Fujimori tamed hyperinflation,reversed
Peru's pariah image with international lenders and implemented
liberal, free-market policies with remarkable success. Growth
averaged more than 7 percent annually, but the trend ended in his
second term, as Asian financial turmoil spread throughout Latin
America and Peru was rocked by the El Nino weather phenomenon.
About half the population lives in poverty and only one in two
people in the labor force has steady work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (RPT With Corrections) News Analysis: Blix Seeks to Make UNMOVIC Different From UNSCOM  (by Xie Meihua) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Hans Blix, executive
chairman of the United Nations Monitoring, Verification and
Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC) for Iraq, presented a report to
the United Nations Thursday, mapping out a blueprint for the staff
structure of the new U.N. arms regime.
</P>
<P>
The UNMOVIC was created by Security Council Resolution 1284
adopted last December to replace the now defunct United Nations
Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction and resume the U.N. arms inspection in
Iraq which has been suspended since the U.S-led military strikes
against the country in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to Blix's plan, there will be no deputy post for the
UNMOVIC, but an executive assistant with less power will be set up,
a contrast with the UNSCOM which was headed by Richard Butler.
</P>
<P>
The deputy post of the UNSCOM has been traditionally held by an
American. The last one was Charles Duelfer who reigned in February
after the establishment of the UNMOVIC.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the UNSCOM, Blix recommended in the plan that the
UNMOVIC will be strong on experts and technical personnel rather
than political functionaries. He also proposed a two-step approach
to recruitment of the personnel for the arms regime, with most
UNMOVIC staff being U.N. employees.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM relied mainly on experts picked up and paid by their
government, a practice that resulted in the alleged UNSCOM spying
for the United States which led to the demise of the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
Blix wants his arms staff to firmly act with a clear U.N.
identity and to avoid them from getting orders from outside the U.
N. body.
</P>
<P>
Blix also wants his arms regime to be tightly-controlled and
leakproof, saying the flow of intelligence must be one way.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the agency's public information officer will
ensure that there will be a single authoritative point of contact
with the media, Blix himself or someone gets authorization from
him.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the UNMOVIC has the same rights of the UNSCOM,
with the freedom of movement and immediate, unrestricted access to
any and all areas, facilities, equipment, records and means of
transportation.
</P>
<P>
But he proposed to open a cultural program for his arms staff
which is aimed to train them in understanding national
sensitivities and the proper handling of adversarial situation in
the field.
</P>
<P>
This is what the UNSCOM failed in its operation and this is
also what led to consequent confrontations between the U.N. arms
inspectors and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The proposed plan is an apparent bid of Blix to motivate Iraq
to cooperate with the United Nations and allow the return of the U.
N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Once the plan is approved by the 15-member Security Council,
possibly next week, the next step will be a visit to Iraq. But so
far, Iraq has reiterated that it bans U.N. arms inspectors from
returning unless the sanctions against the country get lifted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
