<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama to Invest $2 Billion in Four Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Panamanian government will
invest more than two billion U.S. dollars in the next four years
to improve the economy and the elemental services for society,
such as health, education, housing, drinking water, and production
means.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Friday by Economy and Finance Minister
Victor Juliao when he presented his plan of economic, social, and
financial development, with investment in human capital before the
Ninth International Banking Convention.
</P>
<P>
The economic plan is an instrument of the state to solve the
most oppressing problems faced by Panamanian citizens, especially
the 37 percent of the population who lives in a state of poverty
and the 17 percent which suffers extreme poverty, said Juliao.
</P>
<P>
The plan foresees to invest 249 million dollars in the
agriculture sector to improve the quality of the products for
export and also other 39 million dollars for irrigation programs.
</P>
<P>
The program includes the investment of 451 million dollars in
health, 140 million for housing, 303 million in education, and 357
million for the construction of a second bridge over or a tunnel
under the Panama Canal, among other projects.
</P>
<P>
Juliao said that a lot of money will be necessary to implement
this plan and that Panama cannot ask for more international loans,
because its public has reached 7.7 billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
