<HEADLINE> Europe's Leading Stocks End Week Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Europe's major stock markets
finished with a surge Friday as technology, media and
telecommunication issues rebounded from steep declines earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 rose 1.84 percent to 6,569.9, as a gain of
more than 16 percent for Internet security firm Baltimore
Technology outweighed weakness in defense, banking and food stocks.
</P>
<P>
Media company Pearson surged 17.4 percent after it confirmed it
will combine its television business with the pan-European
broadcaster CLT-Ufa.
</P>
<P>
The merger provided a boost to other media stocks, with
broadcaster Carlton Communication rising 11.9 percent, TV and
hotel owner Granada Group up 7.3 percent, and British Sky
Broadcasting climbed 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
The leading gainer on the FTSE 100 benchmark index was Internet
service provider Freeserve, which surged 18 percent. Hand-held
computer maker Psion rose 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Xetra Dax index rose as gains by tech and insurance
stocks outweighed a weak Dresdner Bank, which fell over 4 percent
despite efforts to control the fallout from its failed merger with
Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Dax index ended at 7,522.2 points, up 75.99 or 1.02 percent,
down 77.19 on the week.
</P>
<P>
Paris shares closed higher when roaring gains in telecoms
equipment maker Alcatel and a clutch of media firms pepped up an
otherwise cautious session.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index closed at 6,308.04 points, up 84.02 or 1.35
percent, 21.99 points up on the week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
