<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says It Is Not Pushing Proposals at Israeli-Palestinian Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We're not at this stage where we think it's appropriate for us
to impose or pressure either party to accept an American plan," U.
S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"There's an enormous amount of work to be done" to reach an
agreement, Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators started a week of talks at
Bolling Air Force Base in Washington on Friday morning as the
target date approached for a framework agreement.
</P>
<P>
The middle-level negotiating teams were led by Odea Eran for
Israel and Yasser Abed Rabbo for the Palestinians. U.S.
negotiators are expected to join the talks later in the day.
</P>
<P>
The framework agreement is meant as a step toward a
comprehensive agreement by September 13 covering all the so-called

final status issues such as the size and status of the Palestinian
territories, Jerusalem, water rights, the fate of Palestinian
refugees and Jewish settlements in the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also were taking up another Israeli withdrawal on
the West Bank. Due in June under a 1995 agreement, the size and
specific stretches of territory to be turned over to the
Palestinian Authority have not be decided.
</P>
<P>
So far, Israel has relinquished 40 percent of the West Bank and
all of Gaza to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The same negotiators met at Bolling for one week last month
without any evidence of either progress or deadlock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McGuinness "Willing" to Attend Bloody Sunday Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior Sinn Fein figure said
Friday that Martin McGuinness is willing to appear at the Bloody
Sunday Inquiry to answer allegations that he fired the shot which
started the killings.
</P>
<P>
Party chairman Mitchel McLaughlin said his colleague had yet to
be invited to the inquiry being heard at Londonderry's Guildhall,
and would respond if he was.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry heard Thursday that McGuinness, a former education
minister in the suspended Northern Irish assembly, could have
fired a gun on the day of the army killings 28 years ago.
</P>
<P>
A Security Service document described as the debriefing of an
informer stated McGuinness had admitted "that he had personally
fired the shot from Rossville Flats in the Bogside that had
precipitated the Bloody Sunday episodes."
</P>
<P>
But McLaughlin poured scorn on the allegation, saying the
allegation emerged from an informer and it was dated 1992 --
exactly 20 years after the event.
</P>
<P>
"We have an unnamed military source and clearly it is an
attempt by military -- who are destroying the evidence as this
inquiry progresses -- to create a diversion from the fact that the
British Army murdered 14 people on the streets," he said.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal was also told that McGuinness -- "widely reputed"
to have been commander of the Provisional IRA in the city at the
time -- had so far refused to cooperate with the new inquiry.
</P>
<P>
McGuinness, a Mid Ulster MP and prominent member of Sinn Fein,
has also denied the inquiry's claims, saying they were "a pathetic
fabrication."
</P>
<P>
The inquiry was set up to look again at the deaths of 14 men
shot by paratroopers during a civil rights march in Derry's
Bogside on January 30, 1972.
</P>
<P>
The claims about McGuinness were made on the eighth day of
public hearings of the Saville Inquiry.
</P>
<P>
The Bloody Sunday Inquiry, chaired by Lord Saville of Newdigate,
has been gathering evidence for the past two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
