<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Appeals for Unity of Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
on Friday appealed for unity in the ruling Zimbabwe African
National Union-Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf) leadership if it was to
remain a formidable party.
</P>
<P>
Lack of unity was destroying the party in some provinces, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing at least 10,000 people at a Zanu-pf rally in
Bindura, about 100 kilometers north of Harare, Mugabe said Zanu-pf
would remain committed to the full sovereignty of the Zimbabwean
people.
</P>
<P>
He said the economic hardships being experienced by the poor
people in the country could not be blamed on the government but
manufacturers who keep on increasing prices of basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
He attacked managers of parastatals such as the National Oil
Company of Zimbabwe for corruption that was ruining the country.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the shortages of fuel and price increases were
temporary problems that would pass soon.
</P>
<P>
"We are going back to the time when the increase of prices of
basic commodities will be controlled by the government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president praised war veterans for invading
white- owned commercial farms, saying they were keeping the
liberation spirit alive.
</P>
<P>
He said white farmers should not resist the action by the war
veterans because some who tried to do so were injured.
</P>
<P>
The former freedom fighters recently invaded at least 700
white-owned farms throughout the country, saying they were hungry
for land.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the war veterans' action had been justified by the
Constitution Amendment Bill passed in Parliament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Bill empowers the government to acquire land compulsorily
without compensation if Britain does not provide the money.
</P>
</TEXT>
