<HEADLINE> S. Africa Gets Support for Ivory Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Endangered Wildlife Trust
(EWT) fully supports South Africa's bid to sell 28 tons of ivory
stock from the Kruger National Park in the country, the EWT's
media manager Rayaan Adriaanse said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Adriaanse said in a statement that the EWT rendered its support
because the ivory had been obtained over the years through natural
mortality and population control measures.
</P>
<P>
The South African team, led by Minister of Environmental
Affairs and Tourism Valli Moosa, will submit application to sell
the tusk to a single buyer at the 11th Conference of the Parties
to the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species
(CITES), which will be held in Nairobi, Kenya, from April 10-20.
</P>
<P>
The sale could yield around 30 million rand (4.9 million U.S.
dollars), which South Africa has undertaken to use for future
elephant conservation management purposes.
</P>
<P>
"The EWT notes that the controlled ivory sales by Botswana,
Namibia and Zimbabwe permitted by CITES after its last meeting in
Harare were conducted responsibly and transparently," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said there was no evidence that the sales caused an increase
in elephant poaching. 
</P>
</TEXT>
