<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (rpt with correction)Largest Air Carrier Calls for PNTR with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 7 (Xinhua) -- In order for the United States
to benefit from China's significant market opening, the United
States must first extend China "Permanent Normal Trading Relations
" (PNTR) status, said United Airlines in a statement Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The United Sates and China are part of a global community and
marketplace," United chairman and chief executive officer Jim
Goodwin said in the statement. "The United States has an historic
opportunity to benefit from the opening of the China market, but
only if China is granted PNTR status. We at the United strongly
believe this must happen soon so that the American people can
benefit from the opportunities that will occur when China enters
the World Trade Organization."
</P>
<P>
Denying China PNTR status does not prevent China from joining
the WTO; it only prevents the United States from having greater
access to China's markets, said the largest air carrier in the
world.
</P>
<P>
United Airlines is seeking to operate more air service to China.
The airline currently offers nonstop flights between San Francisco
and Shanghai five days each week, and is urging the U.S.
Department of Transportation to grant it the two remaining
frequencies it needs to provide daily nonstop service. In June,
United will launch daily nonstop service between San Francisco and
Beijing, and the airline will launch another Shanghai daily
nonstop service next year from Chicago, the company said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000407.0351 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
